{"title_page": "4th Guards Military Base", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=4th Guards Military Base\n|native_name=4-\u044f \u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430\n|image= Medium emblem of the \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0421\u0438\u043b\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438.svg\n|image_size=200px\n|caption=The emblem of the Russian Armed Forces\n|dates=2009&ndash;Present\n|country={{flag|Russia}}\n|allegiance={{flag|Russia}}<br>{{flag|South Ossetia}}\n|branch= [[File:Banner of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation (obverse).svg|20px]] [[Russian Armed Forces]]\n|type=[[Task force]]/Military base\n|role= \n|size= 4,500 soldiers<ref>[http://www.rg.ru/2011/09/29/bazy.html \u0411\u0430\u0437\u044b \u043d\u0430 49 \u043b\u0435\u0442. \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0444\u0435\u0434 \u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0441\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445 \u0432 \u0410\u0431\u0445\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n|command_structure=[[Southern Military District]]\n|garrison=[[Tskhinvali]] \n|garrison_label=Headquarters\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|colors_label=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|battle_honours_label=\n|disbanded=\n|website=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1= Guards Colonel Alexander Kravtsov\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|commander4=\n|commander4_label=\n|notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n|identification_symbol_2_label=\n|identification_symbol_3=\n|identification_symbol_3_label=\n|identification_symbol_4=\n|identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\nThe '''4th Guards Military Base''' ({{Lang-ru|4-\u044f \u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430}}) is a sizable overseas [[military base]] of the [[Russian Armed Forces]] stationed in the partially recognized [[Republic of South Ossetia]]. The base is subordinate to the command of the [[Southern Military District]] of the [[Russian Armed Forces]]. It was the first military of strategic importance in the Caucasus.<ref name=\"tanks\">{{cite book|title=The Tanks of August|publisher=Centre for Analysis of Strategies and Technologies|year=2010|chapter=Post-war Deployment of Russian Forces in Abkhazia and South Ossetia|last1=Lavrov|first1=Anton|editor=Ruslan Pukhov|isbn=978-5-9902320-1-3}}</ref> The base is located in the city of Tskhinval and the neighboring village of [[Java (town)|Java]].\n\n==History==\nAfter the [[1991\u20131992 South Ossetia War]], a [[Joint Control Commission for Georgian\u2013Ossetian Conflict Resolution|Joint Control Commission]] was created on the basis of the Dagomys agreement from representatives of four parties: [[Georgia (country)|Georiga]], [[South Ossetia]], [[Russia]] and [[North Ossetia]]. From 1993 to 2008, the Mixed Peacekeeping Forces (consisting of three battalions - Russian, Georgian and Ossetian) were deployed in South Ossetia. Before the war of 2008, Georgian peacekeepers who were part of the Joint Staff of the JPKF left it's command. After the [[Russo-Georgian War]], the Joint Peacekeeping Force ceased to exist.<ref>[http://www.ancentr.ru/data/events/event2008.html \u042e\u0436\u043d\u0430\u044f \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u044f: \u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044f\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f]</ref> After the recognition of the Republic of South Ossetia by Russia, it was decided that a permanent Russian military base was needed.<ref>[http://ria.ru/press_video/20080905/151530504.html \u041e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0410\u0431\u0445\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\nThe base was formed on 1 February 2009 on the basis of the 693rd Guards and 135th Motor Rifle Regiments of the [[19th Motor Rifle Division]] based in [[Vladikavkaz]].<ref>[http://www.rsonews.org/ru/news/20110416/02994.html \u041d\u0430 4-\u0439 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0435 \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u044b \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0431\u044b]</ref> On 7 April 2010, Russian Defence Minister [[Anatoly Serdyukov]] and [[Ministry of Defence (South Ossetia)|South Ossetian Defence Minister]] Yuri Tanayev signed an agreement on a unified Russian military base on the territory of South Ossetia.<ref>[http://www.georgiatimes.info/news/33649.html \u0426\u0445\u0438\u043d\u0432\u0430\u043b: \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430\u00a0\u2014 \u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0433\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0431\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u042e\u041e]</ref><ref>[http://www.kp.ru/daily/24469/629042/ \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044e\u043a\u043e\u0432, \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u0424: \u00ab\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u0431\u044f \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0443\u044e \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u0443 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438\u00bb]</ref> In accordance with the Russian-South Ossetian agreement, the united military base included former peacekeeping facilities in Tskhinval, a training ground in Dzartsem, and a military camp 4 kilometer north of Tskhinval. The [[Russian Airborne Troops]] also established an active military base outside of [[Java, South Ossetia|Java]]. The period of operation of the base is 49 years, with the possibility of automatic renewal for subsequent 15-year periods. On 16 December  2011, the 4th Guards Military Base was awarded the [[Order of St. George]] by President [[Dmitry Medvedev|Medvedev]].<ref>[http://function.mil.ru/news_page/country/more.htm?id=10851500@egNews \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0435 \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u0440\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u044f : \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438]</ref> In 2012, it was planned to form the so-called \"Ossetian Battalion\" recruited from among the [[Armed Forces of South Ossetia]] as part of the base.<ref>[http://www.ng.ru/cis/2012-02-15/7_osetia.html \u0412 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435 4-\u0439 \u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u044b \u0412\u0421 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043e\u043d]</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n[[File:CombatReadiness2017-03.jpg|thumb|Troops of the military base during an exercise in 2017.]]\n{{Col div}}\n* Headquarters;\n* 1st Motorized Rifle Battalion\n* 2nd Motorized Rifle Battalion\n* 3rd Motorized Rifle Battalion\n* Special Forces Bttalion\n* Sniper Company \n* Tank Battalion\n* 1st Self-propelled Artillery Division\n* 2nd Self-propelled Artillery Division\n* Rocket Artillery Division\n* Anti-tank Artillery Division\n* Anti-aircraft Missile and Artillery Division\n* Reconnaissance Battalion\n* [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|Drone]] Company\n* Engineering Battalion\n* [[Russian NBC Protection Troops|NBC Protection]] Company\n* Signals Battalion\n* Electronic Warfare Company \n* Artillery Battery \n* Radar Platoon \n* Intelligence Platoon \n* Repair Battalion\n* Support Battalion\n* commandant company;\n* Medical Company\n* Instructor Platoon\n* Training Platoon\n* Polygon\n* [[Military Band]]\n{{Col div end}}\n\n==Commanders==\n*Major General Alexander Shushukin (February 2009 - October 2013) \n*Colonel Mikhail Polishchuk  Ivanovich (October 2013 - September 2016-) \n*Colonel Alexander Kravtsov (September 2016 - Present)<ref>[http://sputnik-ossetia.ru/South_Ossetia/20160922/3064963.html \u0412\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0430 \u0441 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Russian military bases abroad]]\n*[[Operational Group of Russian Forces]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Army units and formations of Russia]]\n[[Category:Military installations of Russia in other countries]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Military of South Ossetia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=4th Guards Military Base\n|native_name=4-\u044f \u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430\n|image= Medium emblem of the \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0421\u0438\u043b\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438.svg\n|image_size=200px\n|caption=The emblem of the Russian Armed Forces\n|dates=2009&ndash;Present\n|country={{flag|Russia}}\n|allegiance={{flag|Russia}}<br>{{flag|South Ossetia}}\n|branch= [[File:Banner of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation (obverse).svg|20px]] [[Russian Armed Forces]]\n|type=[[Task force]]/Military base\n|role= \n|size= 4,500 soldiers<ref>[http://www.rg.ru/2011/09/29/bazy.html \u0411\u0430\u0437\u044b \u043d\u0430 49 \u043b\u0435\u0442. \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0444\u0435\u0434 \u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0441\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445 \u0432 \u0410\u0431\u0445\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n|command_structure=[[Southern Military District]]\n|garrison=[[Tskhinvali]] \n|garrison_label=Headquarters\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|colors_label=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|battle_honours_label=\n|disbanded=\n|website=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1= Guards Colonel Alexander Kravtsov\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|commander4=\n|commander4_label=\n|notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n|identification_symbol_2_label=\n|identification_symbol_3=\n|identification_symbol_3_label=\n|identification_symbol_4=\n|identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\nThe '''4th Guards Military Base''' ({{Lang-ru|4-\u044f \u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430}}) is a sizable overseas [[military base]] of the [[Russian Armed Forces]] stationed in the partially recognized [[Republic of South Ossetia]]. The base is subordinate to the command of the [[Southern Military District]] of the [[Russian Armed Forces]]. It was the first military of strategic importance in the Caucasus.<ref name=\"tanks\">{{cite book|title=The Tanks of August|publisher=Centre for Analysis of Strategies and Technologies|year=2010|chapter=Post-war Deployment of Russian Forces in Abkhazia and South Ossetia|last1=Lavrov|first1=Anton|editor=Ruslan Pukhov|isbn=978-5-9902320-1-3}}</ref> The base is located in the city of Tskhinval and the neighboring village of [[Java (town)|Java]].\n\n==History==\nAfter the [[1991\u20131992 South Ossetia War]], a [[Joint Control Commission for Georgian\u2013Ossetian Conflict Resolution|Joint Control Commission]] was created on the basis of the Dagomys agreement from representatives of four parties: [[Georgia (country)|Georiga]], [[South Ossetia]], [[Russia]] and [[North Ossetia]]. From 1993 to 2008, the Mixed Peacekeeping Forces (consisting of three battalions - Russian, Georgian and Ossetian) were deployed in South Ossetia. Before the war of 2008, Georgian peacekeepers who were part of the Joint Staff of the JPKF left it's command. After the [[Russo-Georgian War]], the Joint Peacekeeping Force ceased to exist.<ref>[http://www.ancentr.ru/data/events/event2008.html \u042e\u0436\u043d\u0430\u044f \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u044f: \u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044f\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f]</ref> After the recognition of the Republic of South Ossetia by Russia, it was decided that a permanent Russian military base was needed.<ref>[http://ria.ru/press_video/20080905/151530504.html \u041e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0410\u0431\u0445\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\nThe base was formed on 1 February 2009 on the basis of the 693rd Guards and 135th Motor Rifle Regiments of the [[19th Motor Rifle Division]] based in [[Vladikavkaz]].<ref>[http://www.rsonews.org/ru/news/20110416/02994.html \u041d\u0430 4-\u0439 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0435 \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u044b \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0431\u044b]</ref> On 7 April 2010, Russian Defence Minister [[Anatoly Serdyukov]] and [[Ministry of Defence (South Ossetia)|South Ossetian Defence Minister]] Yuri Tanayev signed an agreement on a unified Russian military base on the territory of South Ossetia.<ref>[http://www.georgiatimes.info/news/33649.html \u0426\u0445\u0438\u043d\u0432\u0430\u043b: \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430\u00a0\u2014 \u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0433\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0431\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u042e\u041e]</ref><ref>[http://www.kp.ru/daily/24469/629042/ \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044e\u043a\u043e\u0432, \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u0424: \u00ab\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u0431\u044f \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0443\u044e \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u0443 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438\u00bb]</ref> In accordance with the Russian-South Ossetian agreement, the united military base included former peacekeeping facilities in Tskhinval, a training ground in Dzartsem, and a military camp 4 kilometer north of Tskhinval. The [[Russian Airborne Troops]] also established an active military base outside of [[Java, South Ossetia|Java]]. The period of operation of the base is 49 years, with the possibility of automatic renewal for subsequent 15-year periods. On 16 December  2011, the 4th Guards Military Base was awarded the [[Order of St. George]] by President [[Dmitry Medvedev|Medvedev]].<ref>[http://function.mil.ru/news_page/country/more.htm?id=10851500@egNews \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0435 \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u0440\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u044f : \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438]</ref> In 2012, it was planned to form the so-called \"Ossetian Battalion\" recruited from among the [[Armed Forces of South Ossetia]] as part of the base.<ref>[http://www.ng.ru/cis/2012-02-15/7_osetia.html \u0412 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435 4-\u0439 \u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u044b \u0412\u0421 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043e\u043d]</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n[[File:CombatReadiness2017-03.jpg|thumb|Troops of the military base during an exercise in 2017.]]\n{{Col div}}\n* Headquarters;\n* 1st Motorized Rifle Battalion\n* 2nd Motorized Rifle Battalion\n* 3rd Motorized Rifle Battalion\n* Special Forces Bttalion\n* Sniper Company \n* Tank Battalion\n* 1st Self-propelled Artillery Division\n* 2nd Self-propelled Artillery Division\n* Rocket Artillery Division\n* Anti-tank Artillery Division\n* Anti-aircraft Missile and Artillery Division\n* Reconnaissance Battalion\n* [[Drone]] Company\n* Engineering Battalion\n* [[Russian NBC Protection Troops|NBC Protection]] Company\n* Signals Battalion\n* Electronic Warfare Company \n* Artillery Battery \n* Radar Platoon \n* Intelligence Platoon \n* Repair Battalion\n* Support Battalion\n* commandant company;\n* Medical Company\n* Instructor Platoon\n* Training Platoon\n* Polygon\n* [[Military Band]]\n{{Col div end}}\n\n==Commanders==\n*Major General Alexander Shushukin (February 2009 - October 2013) \n*Colonel Mikhail Polishchuk  Ivanovich (October 2013 - September 2016-) \n*Colonel Alexander Kravtsov (September 2016 - Present)<ref>[http://sputnik-ossetia.ru/South_Ossetia/20160922/3064963.html \u0412\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0430 \u0441 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Russian military bases abroad]]\n*[[Operational Group of Russian Forces]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Army units and formations of Russia]]\n[[Category:Military installations of Russia in other countries]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Military of South Ossetia]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDrone(link changed toUnmanned aerial vehicle) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/4th_Guards_Military_Base"}
{"title_page": "Bruno Reichart", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical person | honorific_prefix =Professor  | name = Bruno Reichart | honorific_suffix =  | image = Bruno Reichart (TRR).jpg | image_size =  | alt =  | caption =  | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|01|18|df=y}} | birth_place =  | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  --> | death_place =  | death_cause =  | nationality =  | citizenship =  | education =*[[University of Erlangen\u2013Nuremberg]] \n*[[Munich University]] | occupation =[[Cardiothoracic surgeon]] | years_active =  | known_for = Performed Germany's \n*first [[heart transplant]] in 1981\n*first combined [[heart\u2013lung transplant]] in 1983| relations =  | website =  | profession =  | field =  | work_institutions =  | specialism =  | research_field =  | notable_works =  | prizes =  | child =  | module2 =  | signature =  }}\n\n'''Bruno Reichart''' (born 18 January 1943) is a retired German [[cardiothoracic surgeon]] who performed Germany's first successful [[heart transplant]] in 1981 and its first combined [[heart\u2013lung transplant]] in 1983.\n\nIn 1984, he succeeded [[Christiaan Barnard]] at [[Groote Schuur Hospital]] in Cape Town and was appointed president of the [[International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation]] (ISHLT) from 1988 to 1990. He returned to Munich in 1990 as director of the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the [[Klinikum Gro\u00dfhadern]] of the University of Munich (LMU).\n\nHe has also been active in experimental research in [[xenotransplantation]] and from 2011 became a spokesman for funded research into the transplantation of pig tissue and organs into [[primates]], with a team involving [[veterinarians]], [[virologists]], clinicians, lawyers and [[ethicists]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBruno Reichart was born in Vienna in 1943<ref name=Whoswho>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whoswho.de/bio/bruno-reichart.html|title=Bruno Reichart - Biografie WHO'S WHO|website=www.whoswho.de|language=German|access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref> and grew up in [[Ingolstadt]].<ref name=CV2016>{{Cite news|url=https://bdo-ev.de/uploads/media/Lebenslauf_Reichart.pdf|title=BrunoReichart- Curriculum Vitae|last=|first=|date=2016|work=|access-date=15 November 2018}}</ref> He studied medicine at the [[University of Erlangen\u2013Nuremberg]] and [[Munich University]], now called Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich (LMU)<ref name=Whoswho/> and received his [[Doctor of medicine|MD]] in 1968, after which he became a medical assistant at the First Gynecological Clinic of the University of Munich, the Surgical Department of the [[Klinikum der Universit\u00e4t M\u00fcnchen|Municipal Hospital Munich-Harlaching]] and at the Medical Clinic of the University of Munich.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n==Early surgical career==\nFrom 1971 to 1973, Reichart worked as a surgical assistant under surgeon [[Rudolf Zenker]]<ref name=Whoswho/><ref name=izb2018/> and within a year was appointed visiting cardiac physician in Memphis, Tennessee, where he focused on heart, lung, and [[vascular surgery]].<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\nUpon his return to Munich in 1974, Reichart commenced surgery at the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the LMU. In 1977 he became its senior physician and a year later he passed his [[habilitation]] with the topic \"The mechanical support of acute right heart failure\",<ref name=CV2016/> and become a cardiothoracic surgeon in 1978.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n===Heart transplant 1981===\nOn 19 August 1981, Reichart performed Germany's first successful heart transplant at the LMU.<ref name=\"Unger2012\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=msjqCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA334|title=Assisted Circulation 2|last1=Reichart|first1=B|last2=Uberfuhr|first2=P|last3=Welz|first3=A|last4=B. M. Kemkes|first4=B. M.|last5=Kreuzer|first5=E.|last6=Klinner|first6=W.|last7=Reble|first7=B.|last8=Funccius|first8=W.|last9=Hammer|first9=C.|publisher=Springer-Verlag|others=W. Ertel H. Reichenspurner D. Peters M. Gokel N. Franke W. Land|year=1984|isbn=978-3-642-69477-6|editor=Felix Unger|location=|page=334|chapter=23. New Beginnings with Heart and Heart-Lung Transplantation at the University of Munich}}</ref> The procedure was previously performed more than 10 years earlier in 1969, when two heart transplants took place in the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the LMU,<ref name=dgthg/><ref name=\"KillyVierhaus2011\">{{cite book|last1=Killy|first1=Walther |last2=Vierhaus|first2=Rudolf |title=Thibaut - Zycha|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1NVRfl4gCw0C&pg=PA676|year=2011|publisher=De Gruyter|isbn=978-3-598-23290-9|page=676}}</ref> but they were both unsuccessful,<ref name=dgthg>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dgthg.de/en/node/117|title=The history of cardiac surgery {{!}} Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Thorax-, Herz- und Gef\u00e4\u00dfchirurgie|website=www.dgthg.de|access-date=13 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=Birks2002>{{Cite journal|last=Bircks|first=W|date=2002|title=History of cardiac surgery in Germany \u2013 in consideration of her relation to the German Cardiac Society|journal=Z Kardiol|volume=91|pages=84\u20138|doi=10.1007/s00392-002-1413-y|pmid=12641020}}</ref> with one dying within two days of surgery, from a [[coronary thrombosis]].<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> Reichart's attempt in 1981 involved a 32-year old recipient who had experienced a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] a year earlier and was left with severely [[heart failure|impaired left ventricular function]]. During the year until heart transplant, the recipient also experienced a large [[pulmonary embolus|blood clot in the lung]], [[congestive cardiac failure|acute heart failure]] and a [[stomach ulcer]]. The 23 year  old donor had been killed in a road traffic accident ten days prior to transplant. [[Azathioprine]], [[cortisone]] and [[Anti-thymocyte globulin]] were the [[immunosuppressants]] used until two [[organ rejection|rejection]] episodes resulted in changing therapy to [[cyclosporine A]] three weeks after surgery<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> and they were discharged from hospital at Christmas 1981.<ref name=Uberfuhr1982>{{Cite journal|last=Uberfuhr|first=P.|last2=Reichart|first2=B.|last3=Welz|first3=A.|last4=Kreuzer|first4=E.|last5=Kemkes|first5=B. M.|last6=Klinner|first6=W.|last7=Hammer|first7=C.|last8=Ertel|first8=W.|last9=Reichenspurner|first9=H.|date=1982-12-01|title=[Report on a successful orthotopic cardiac transplantation in Germany]|journal=Klinische Wochenschrift|volume=60|issue=23|pages=1435\u20131442|issn=0023-2173|pmid=6759785|doi=10.1007/bf01720990}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1978 and 1982, he held various professorships including the Universities of Boston, Birmingham, Milwaukee, Paris and Stanford.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\nMore than twenty heart transplant procedures followed over the next three years.<ref name=\"Klinikum\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.klinikum.uni-muenchen.de/SFB-TRR-127/de/news_and_events/news/Archiv-News/2015-nice-pioneer-award/index.html|title=Nice, Prof. Bruno Reichart awarded with Pioneer Award Nice / South of France, Klinikum Gro\u00dfhadern M\u00fcnchen|website=www.klinikum.uni-muenchen.de|language=de|access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref> Under his leadership, intermittently spanning over 40 years at LMU, more than 1,000 heart transplants were performed.<ref name=izb2018>{{Cite news|url=https://www.izb-online.de/files/Inhalte/izb-im-dialog/izb_im_dialog_2018_01/IZB_ImDialog_1_2018_prof-reichart.pdf|title=Wiesieht die Transplantations medizin der Zukunft aus|last=Simon|first=Susanne|date=2018|work=Spitzenforscher Auf Dem Campus (Top researchers at the Campus)|access-date=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Combined heart-lung transplant 1983===\nOn 13 February 1983,<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> Reichart was the first in Germany to perform a combined [[heart\u2013lung transplant]].<ref name=Klinikum/><ref name=dpz>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dpz.eu/en/unit/about-experimental-animal-research/erfolge-der-forschung/therapies-based-on-animal-research/xenotransplantation.html|title=Deutsches Primatenzentrum: Xenotransplantation|website=www.dpz.eu|language=de|access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref> The recipient was 27 years old and bed-bound with severe [[pulmonary hypertension]] and diseased liver and kidneys. The donor, three years younger, had died the previous day from a [[subdural haematoma|clot in the brain]]. Following the combined heart\u2013lung transplant, the recipient died after ten days.<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> Reichart was appointed professor at the LMU in the same year.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n==Later surgical career==\n[[File:Groote Schuur Hospital, Observatory, Cape Town, Western Cape. 05.JPG|thumb|Groote Schuur Hospital]]\nIn 1984 he became a cardiac surgeon at the South African [[Groote Schuur Hospital]] in Cape Town, succeeding [[Christiaan Barnard]].<ref name=Whoswho/> Here, his research on baboons and green monkeys had been discontinued due to problems with its acceptance from society and the universities.<ref name=izb2018/>\n\nIn 1990, he returned to Munich and was appointed director of the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the [[Klinikum Gro\u00dfhadern]] of the LMU.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n===Xenotransplantation===\nIn 2011, he became a spokesman for funded research into the transplantation of pig tissue and organs into primates (xenotransplantation,)<ref name=izb2018/><ref name=\"Jox2015\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OPJUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA220&dq=Bruno+Reichart#v=onepage&q=Bruno%20Reichart&f=false|title=Organ Transplantation in Times of Donor Shortage: Challenges and Solutions|last=Jox|first=Ralf J.|last2=Assadi|first2=Galia|last3=Marckmann|first3=Georg|date=2015|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-16440-3|location=Munich|pages=220|language=en}}</ref> leading a group that develops [[Genetically modified mammal|transgenic]] pigs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/540076/surgeons-smash-records-with-pig-to-primate-organ-transplants/|title=Transgenic Pigs Shatter Transplant Records|last=Regalado|first=Antonio|date=12 August 2015|work=MIT Technology Review|access-date=14 November 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nTo prevent [[hyperacute rejection]] and coagulation disorders, harmful pig genes are replaced with certain human genes. This German Research Foundation (DFG) funded research, the \u201cBiology of xenogeneic cell, tissue, and organ transplantation \u2013 from basic research to clinical application\u201d has involved collaborating with [[veterinarians]], [[virologists]], clinicians, lawyers and [[ethicists]].<ref name=izb2018/>\n\nAt his 75th birthday celebrations in 2018, he anticipated that it would take at least three years before the first human would be implanted with a pig\u2019s heart.<ref name=izb2018/> His aspiration is to see that \"the transplanted tissues and organs will in the future be genetically programmed to also carry an immunosuppressive molecule on all their cells, so that even fewer corresponding drugs are needed - or perhaps none at all\".<ref name=izb2018/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nReichart was president of the ISHLT from 1988 to 1990,<ref name=Whoswho/><ref name=ISHLTPresidents>[https://www.ishlt.org/about-ishlt/board-of-directors/past-presidents-forum/past-presidents Past Presidents.] International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation. Retrieved 8 July 2018.</ref> who honoured him with the Pioneer Award for his work in heart surgery in Munich at their 35th annual meeting<ref name=Klinikum/> in 2015.<ref name=\"ISHLT2015\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uHS7CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT45&dq=Bruno+Reichart#v=onepage&q=Bruno%20Reichart&f=false|title=ISHLT 2016 Final Program: 36th Annual Meeting and Scientific Sessions|last=Transplantation|first=International Society for Heart and Lung|date=2016-03-15|publisher=CTI Meeting Technology|language=en}}</ref> He holds emeritus membership of the society.<ref name=\"ISHLT2015\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n===Books===\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=shclAAAAMAAJ&q=Bruno+Reichart&dq=Bruno+Reichart&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio_OHks8_eAhXKJ8AKHeJkBAk4ChDoAQguMAI ''Crossing the Borders in Heart Surgery: Simple Thoughts''], [[University of Cape Town]], 1985, {{ISBN|9780799209723}}.\n\n===Articles===\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 26306448 | doi = 10.1007/978-3-319-18603-0_9 | volume=865 | title=Xenotransplantation of Cells, Tissues, Organs and the German Research Foundation Transregio Collaborative Research Centre 127 | year=2015 | journal=Adv Exp Med Biol | pages=143\u201355 | last1 = Reichart | first1 = B | last2 = Guethoff | first2 = S | last3 = Brenner | first3 = P | last4 = Poettinger | first4 = T | last5 = Wolf | first5 = E | last6 = Ludwig | first6 = B | last7 = Kind | first7 = A | last8 = Mayr | first8 = T | last9 = Abicht | first9 = JM}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 28437287 | doi = 10.1097/TP.0000000000001800 | volume=101 | title=Allocation of Organs Should be Based on the Current Status of Medical Science | pmc=5542785 | year=2017 | journal=Transplantation | pages=e283-e284 | last1 = Reichart | first1 = B | last2 = Schroth | first2 = U | last3 = Jauch | first3 = KW}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reichart, Bruno}}\n[[Category:German thoracic surgeons]]\n[[Category:German transplant surgeons]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:University of Erlangen-Nuremberg alumni]]\n[[Category:Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich alumni]]\n[[Category:Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich faculty]]\n[[Category:History of heart surgery]]\n[[Category:History of transplant surgery]]\n[[Category:1981 in medicine]]\n[[Category:1983 in medicine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical person | honorific_prefix =Professor  | name = Bruno Reichart | honorific_suffix =  | image = Bruno Reichart (TRR).jpg | image_size =  | alt =  | caption =  | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|01|18|df=y}} | birth_place =  | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  --> | death_place =  | death_cause =  | nationality =  | citizenship =  | education =*[[University of Erlangen\u2013Nuremberg]] \n*[[Munich University]] | occupation =[[Cardiothoracic surgeon]] | years_active =  | known_for = Performed Germany's \n*first [[heart transplant]] in 1981\n*first combined [[heart\u2013lung transplant]] in 1983| relations =  | website =  | profession =  | field =  | work_institutions =  | specialism =  | research_field =  | notable_works =  | prizes =  | child =  | module2 =  | signature =  }}\n\n'''Bruno Reichart''' (born 18 January 1943) is a retired German [[cardiothoracic surgeon]] who performed Germany's first successful [[heart transplant]] in 1981 and its first combined [[heart\u2013lung transplant]] in 1983.\n\nIn 1984, he succeeded [[Christiaan Barnard]] at [[Groote Schuur Hospital]] in Cape Town and was appointed president of the [[International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation]] (ISHLT) from 1988 to 1990. He returned to Munich in 1990 as director of the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the [[Klinikum Gro\u00dfhadern]] of the University of Munich (LMU).\n\nHe has also been active in experimental research in [[xenotransplantation]] and from 2011 became a spokesman for funded research into the transplantation of pig tissue and organs into [[primates]], with a team involving [[veterinarians]], [[virologists]], clinicians, lawyers and [[ethicists]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBruno Reichart was born in Vienna in 1943<ref name=Whoswho>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whoswho.de/bio/bruno-reichart.html|title=Bruno Reichart - Biografie WHO'S WHO|website=www.whoswho.de|language=German|access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref> and grew up in [[Ingolstadt]].<ref name=CV2016>{{Cite news|url=https://bdo-ev.de/uploads/media/Lebenslauf_Reichart.pdf|title=BrunoReichart- Curriculum Vitae|last=|first=|date=2016|work=|access-date=15 November 2018}}</ref> He studied medicine at the [[University of Erlangen\u2013Nuremberg]] and [[Munich University]], now called Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich (LMU)<ref name=Whoswho/> and received his [[Doctor of medicine|MD]] in 1968, after which he became a medical assistant at the First Gynecological Clinic of the University of Munich, the Surgical Department of the [[Klinikum der Universit\u00e4t M\u00fcnchen|Municipal Hospital Munich-Harlaching]] and at the Medical Clinic of the University of Munich.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n==Early surgical career==\nFrom 1971 to 1973, Reichart worked as a surgical assistant under surgeon [[Rudolf Zenker]]<ref name=Whoswho/><ref name=izb2018/> and within a year was appointed visiting cardiac physician in Memphis, Tennessee, where he focused on heart, lung, and [[vascular surgery]].<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\nUpon his return to Munich in 1974, Reichart commenced surgery at the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the LMU. In 1977 he became its senior physician and a year later he passed his [[habilitation]] with the topic \"The mechanical support of acute right heart failure\",<ref name=CV2016/> and become a cardiothoracic surgeon in 1978.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n===Heart transplant 1981===\nOn 19 August 1981, Reichart performed Germany's first successful heart transplant at the LMU.<ref name=\"Unger2012\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=msjqCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA334|title=Assisted Circulation 2|last1=Reichart|first1=B|last2=Uberfuhr|first2=P|last3=Welz|first3=A|last4=B. M. Kemkes|first4=B. M.|last5=Kreuzer|first5=E.|last6=Klinner|first6=W.|last7=Reble|first7=B.|last8=Funccius|first8=W.|last9=Hammer|first9=C.|publisher=Springer-Verlag|others=W. Ertel H. Reichenspurner D. Peters M. Gokel N. Franke W. Land|year=1984|isbn=978-3-642-69477-6|editor=Felix Unger|location=|page=334|chapter=23. New Beginnings with Heart and Heart-Lung Transplantation at the University of Munich}}</ref> The procedure was previously performed more than 10 years earlier in 1969, when two heart transplants took place in the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the LMU,<ref name=dgthg/><ref name=\"KillyVierhaus2011\">{{cite book|last1=Killy|first1=Walther |last2=Vierhaus|first2=Rudolf |title=Thibaut - Zycha|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1NVRfl4gCw0C&pg=PA676|year=2011|publisher=De Gruyter|isbn=978-3-598-23290-9|page=676}}</ref> but they were both unsuccessful,<ref name=dgthg>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dgthg.de/en/node/117|title=The history of cardiac surgery {{!}} Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Thorax-, Herz- und Gef\u00e4\u00dfchirurgie|website=www.dgthg.de|access-date=13 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=Birks2002>{{Cite journal|last=Bircks|first=W|date=2002|title=History of cardiac surgery in Germany \u2013 in consideration of her relation to the German Cardiac Society|journal=Z Kardiol|volume=91|pages=84\u20138|doi=10.1007/s00392-002-1413-y|pmid=12641020}}</ref> with one dying within two days of surgery, from a [[coronary thrombosis]].<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> Reichart's attempt in 1981 involved a 32-year old recipient who had experienced a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] a year earlier and was left with severely [[heart failure|impaired left ventricular function]]. During the year until heart transplant, the recipient also experienced a large [[pulmonary embolus|blood clot in the lung]], [[congestive cardiac failure|acute heart failure]] and a [[stomach ulcer]]. The 23 year  old donor had been killed in a road traffic accident ten days prior to transplant. [[Azathioprine]], [[cortisone]] and [[Anti-thymocyte globulin]] were the [[immunosuppressants]] used until two [[organ rejection|rejection]] episodes resulted in changing therapy to [[cyclosporine A]] three weeks after surgery<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> and they were discharged from hospital at Christmas 1981.<ref name=Uberfuhr1982>{{Cite journal|last=Uberfuhr|first=P.|last2=Reichart|first2=B.|last3=Welz|first3=A.|last4=Kreuzer|first4=E.|last5=Kemkes|first5=B. M.|last6=Klinner|first6=W.|last7=Hammer|first7=C.|last8=Ertel|first8=W.|last9=Reichenspurner|first9=H.|date=1982-12-01|title=[Report on a successful orthotopic cardiac transplantation in Germany]|journal=Klinische Wochenschrift|volume=60|issue=23|pages=1435\u20131442|issn=0023-2173|pmid=6759785|doi=10.1007/bf01720990}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1978 and 1982, he held various professorships including the Universities of Boston, Birmingham, Milwaukee, Paris and Stanford.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\nMore than twenty heart transplant procedures followed over the next three years.<ref name=\"Klinikum\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.klinikum.uni-muenchen.de/SFB-TRR-127/de/news_and_events/news/Archiv-News/2015-nice-pioneer-award/index.html|title=Nice, Prof. Bruno Reichart awarded with Pioneer Award Nice / South of France, Klinikum Gro\u00dfhadern M\u00fcnchen|website=www.klinikum.uni-muenchen.de|language=de|access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref> Under his leadership, intermittently spanning over 40 years at LMU, more than 1,000 heart transplants were performed.<ref name=izb2018>{{Cite news|url=https://www.izb-online.de/files/Inhalte/izb-im-dialog/izb_im_dialog_2018_01/IZB_ImDialog_1_2018_prof-reichart.pdf|title=Wiesieht die Transplantations medizin der Zukunft aus|last=Simon|first=Susanne|date=2018|work=Spitzenforscher Auf Dem Campus (Top researchers at the Campus)|access-date=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Combined heart-lung transplant 1983===\nOn 13 February 1983,<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> Reichart was the first in Germany to perform a combined [[heart\u2013lung transplant]].<ref name=Klinikum/><ref name=dpz>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dpz.eu/en/unit/about-experimental-animal-research/erfolge-der-forschung/therapies-based-on-animal-research/xenotransplantation.html|title=Deutsches Primatenzentrum: Xenotransplantation|website=www.dpz.eu|language=de|access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref> The recipient was 27 years old and bed-bound with severe [[pulmonary hypertension]] and diseased liver and kidneys. The donor, three years younger, had died the previous day from a [[subdural haematoma|clot in the brain]]. Following the combined heart\u2013lung transplant, the recipient died after ten days.<ref name=\"Unger2012\"/> Reichart was appointed professor at the LMU in the same year.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n==Later surgical career==\n[[File:Groote Schuur Hospital, Observatory, Cape Town, Western Cape. 05.JPG|thumb|Groote Schuur Hospital]]\nIn 1984 he became a cardiac surgeon at the South African [[Groote Schuur Hospital]] in Cape Town, succeeding [[Christiaan Barnard]].<ref name=Whoswho/> Here, his research on baboons and green monkeys had been discontinued due to problems with its acceptance from society and the universities.<ref name=izb2018/>\n\nIn 1990, he returned to Munich and was appointed director of the Cardiac Surgery Clinic at the [[Klinikum Gro\u00dfhadern]] of the LMU.<ref name=Whoswho/>\n\n===Xenotransplantation===\nIn 2011, he became a spokesman for funded research into the transplantation of pig tissue and organs into primates (xenotransplantation,)<ref name=izb2018/><ref name=\"Jox2015\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OPJUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA220&dq=Bruno+Reichart#v=onepage&q=Bruno%20Reichart&f=false|title=Organ Transplantation in Times of Donor Shortage: Challenges and Solutions|last=Jox|first=Ralf J.|last2=Assadi|first2=Galia|last3=Marckmann|first3=Georg|date=2015|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-16440-3|location=Munich|pages=220|language=en}}</ref> leading a group that develops [[Genetically modified mammal|transgenic]] pigs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/540076/surgeons-smash-records-with-pig-to-primate-organ-transplants/|title=Transgenic Pigs Shatter Transplant Records|last=Regalado|first=Antonio|date=12 August 2015|work=MIT Technology Review|access-date=14 November 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nTo prevent [[hyperacute rejection]] and coagulation disorders, harmful pig genes are replaced with certain human genes. This German Research Foundation (DFG) funded research, the \u201cBiology of xenogeneic cell, tissue, and organ transplantation \u2013 from basic research to clinical application\u201d has involved collaborating with [[veterinarians]], [[virologists]], clinicians, lawyers and [[ethicists]].<ref name=izb2018/>\n\nAt his 75th birthday celebrations in 2018, he anticipated that it would take at least three years before the first human would be implanted with a pig\u2019s heart.<ref name=izb2018/> His aspiration is to see that \"the transplanted tissues and organs will in the future be genetically programmed to also carry an immunosuppressive molecule on all their cells, so that even fewer corresponding drugs are needed - or perhaps none at all\".<ref name=izb2018/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nReichart was president of the ISHLT from 1988 to 1990,<ref name=Whoswho/><ref name=ISHLTPresidents>[https://www.ishlt.org/about-ishlt/board-of-directors/past-presidents-forum/past-presidents Past Presidents.] International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation. Retrieved 8 July 2018.</ref> who honoured him with the Pioneer Award for his work in heart surgery in Munich at their 35th annual meeting<ref name=Klinikum/> in 2015.<ref name=\"ISHLT2015\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uHS7CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT45&dq=Bruno+Reichart#v=onepage&q=Bruno%20Reichart&f=false|title=ISHLT 2016 Final Program: 36th Annual Meeting and Scientific Sessions|last=Transplantation|first=International Society for Heart and Lung|date=2016-03-15|publisher=CTI Meeting Technology|language=en}}</ref> He holds emeritus membership of the society.<ref name=\"ISHLT2015\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n===Books===\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=shclAAAAMAAJ&q=Bruno+Reichart&dq=Bruno+Reichart&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio_OHks8_eAhXKJ8AKHeJkBAk4ChDoAQguMAI ''Crossing the Borders in Heart Surgery: Simple Thoughts''], [[University of Cape Town]], 1985, {{ISBN|9780799209723}}.\n\n===Articles===\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26306448  \u201cXenotransplantation of Cells, Tissues, Organs and the German Research Foundation Transregio Collaborative Research Centre 127\u201d], Co-authored with Guethoff S, Brenner P, Poettinger T, Wolf E, Ludwig B, Kind A, Mayr T, Abicht JM., ''Advances in Experimental Medicine and Biology'', 2015;865:143-55, {{DOI|10.1007/978-3-319-18603-0_9}}.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5542785/ \u201cAllocation of Organs Should be Based on the Current Status of Medical Science\u201d], co-authored with Ulrich Schroth and Karl-Walter Jauch, ''[[Transplantation (journal)|Transplantation]]'', 2017, {{PMID|28437287}}, {{Doi|10.1097/TP.0000000000001800}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reichart, Bruno}}\n[[Category:German thoracic surgeons]]\n[[Category:German transplant surgeons]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:University of Erlangen-Nuremberg alumni]]\n[[Category:Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich alumni]]\n[[Category:Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich faculty]]\n[[Category:History of heart surgery]]\n[[Category:History of transplant surgery]]\n[[Category:1981 in medicine]]\n[[Category:1983 in medicine]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArticles:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruno_Reichart"}
{"title_page": "Soundtracks for the Blind", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Soundtracks for the Blind\n| type       = studio\n| longtype   = ([[double album]])\n| artist     = [[Swans (band)|Swans]]\n| cover      = Soundtracks for the Blind.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 22 October 1996\n| recorded   = 1981 \u2013 1996\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Experimental rock]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Isachs |title=Recorded Music: Swans, \u201cSoundtracks for the Blind\u201d (Young God, 1996) |url=https://blogs.colum.edu/reviewing-the-arts/2013/03/19/recorded-music-swans-soundtracks-for-the-blind-1996-young-god/ |website=Reviewing the Arts, Columbia College Chicago |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[post-rock]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=joshuatree |title=Swans - Soundtracks for the Blind |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/26462/Swans-Soundtracks-for-the-Blind/ |website=sputnikmusic |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[dark ambient]]\n*[[Drone music|drone]]\n*[[avant-garde]]\n*[[post-industrial]]\n*[[neofolk|avant-folk]]\n*[[field recording]]\n*[[spoken word]]\n*[[sound collage]]\n}}\n| length     = 141:37\n| label      = [[Young God Records|Young God]]\n| producer   = [[Michael Gira]], [[Jarboe]] (track 7)\n| prev_title = [[Die T\u00fcr ist zu]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Swans Are Dead]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Soundtracks for the Blind\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Failure\" / \"Animus\n | single1date = 1996\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Soundtracks for the Blind''''' is the tenth studio album by [[Swans (band)|Swans]], and the last released until 2010's ''[[My Father Will Guide Me up a Rope to the Sky]]''. It was released as a [[Double album|double]] [[Compact disc|CD]] in 1996, through [[Young God Records]]. ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' was intended, as suggested by the title, to function as a sort of \"soundtrack for a non-existent film\", and is Swans' most varied studio effort.\n\nA [[reissue]] of the album was released on July 20, 2018, marking the first time ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' was released on [[Phonograph record|vinyl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://younggodrecords.com/products/soundtracks-2018|title=Soundtracks For The Blind (Remastered 2018) PREORDER|website=YOUNG GOD RECORDS|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nMuch of the album is tied together with audio collage works and sample-based textural pieces recorded at various times and places, as well as the use of previous Swans material (such as the lyrics of \"Your Property\" from ''[[Cop (album)|Cop]]'' for \"YRP\"). On this, frontman Michael Gira said in 1997:\n\n<blockquote>I've always been interested in different sounds like that and listened to [[Brian Eno]] and different kinds of music that use non-musical sources often, and as I made this record I had a lot of that material: those loops and things I'd made from '81; I had vocal loops that Jarboe had made in 1985 on a little sixteen second digital delay unit which was actually the first sampler... we had these tape narrations we'd been collecting, that she got from her father's desk when he was an FBI agent \u2013 surveillance tapes; I interviewed my father because I'm interested in his life, and took a little snippet of his experiences... then we had new things we'd recorded with our 'band' from the last tour; and some stuff we did for a soundtrack for a film. I threw all those into the computer and assembled it that way. So, in some things, there's something from 1981 playing simultaneously with something from '85 playing simultaneously with something from 1996. It's cross-faded and blended and mixed so to speak in the computer, cut-up and sometimes looped and reversed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://younggodrecords.com/press/98-swans/1426-swans-m-gira-interview |title=Swans <nowiki>| M. Gira |</nowiki> Interview |work=[[Young God Records|younggodrecords.com]] |access-date=March 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130210125055/http://younggodrecords.com/press/98-swans/1426-swans-m-gira-interview |archive-date=February 10, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn the Young God Records page for \"Soundtracks for the Blind\", Gira wrote this in 2008 about the general experience of making the album:\n\n<blockquote>This double CD album has everything in there \u2013 all the ideas from Swans\u2019 15 years of work. There\u2019s some contemporary recordings of the band as it existed in \u201896/7, with Larry Mullins on drums/percussion, Jarboe singing and playing keyboards, Vudi playing electric guitar, and Joe Goldring playing bass and electric guitar, and me singing and playing electric and acoustic guitar, but there\u2019s also a huge amount of sounds and recordings that I (and a few by Jarboe here too) collected over the years. These are reassembled, looped, mangled, and in many cases overdubbed upon to create new pieces of music. Being the \u201cartist\u201d in this case, it\u2019s hard for me to talk about this one, because the memory is so laden (or burdened!) with the experience of making this thing. I guess what I\u2019m trying to say here is I almost had a heart attack making it (slightly kidding here). It was just overwhelming. I really set my own trap, dug my own grave on this one. There was SO MUCH material to deal with, to sift through (whole trunks full of decomposing, moldy cassettes and discs with samples and sounds), and the task of making it into something coherent was at times debilitating. Really like climbing up a mountain of sand. I don\u2019t remember why I set this goal for myself, to somehow incorporate such a ridiculously disparate amount of material. I think maybe it was so I could justify throwing all that crap into the local dump, which is what I did when I finished the album. But in the end, after centuries of picking at this huge iceberg of material with a toothpick, my trusty engineer Chris Griffin and I managed to sculpt something out of it. It actually breathes, seems to live, in most places I think. There\u2019s a press release below written by Kurt at Atavistic (Swans label at the time), and some reviews too, which might give you a better idea of how this sounds. Anyway, in the end, I was elated with this music, both because I liked it and because finishing it meant I could finally lay Swans to rest after 15 years. In my case, I\u2019m always happiest when I\u2019m leaving.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://younggodrecords.com/collections/swans/products/soundtracks-for-the-blind |title=Soundtracks for the Blind <nowiki>| M. Gira |</nowiki> Interview |work=[[Young God Records|younggodrecords.com]] |access-date=November 28, 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/HaRzt |archive-date=July 13, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/soundtracks-for-the-blind-mw0000080044 |title=''Soundtracks for the Blind'' \u2013 Swans |last=Raggett |first=Ned |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=March 2, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2score = 5/5<ref name=\"Alternative Press\">{{cite magazine |title=Swans: ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' |magazine=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |issue=103 |date=February 1997 |page=55}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[MusicHound|MusicHound Rock]]''\n| rev3score = 4/5<ref>''MusicHound Rock: The Essential Album Guide'' (1996)</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev4score = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/26462/Swans-Soundtracks-for-the-Blind/ |title=Swans \u2013 ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' |author=joshuatree |work=[[Sputnikmusic]] |date=July 26, 2008 |accessdate=March 2, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Terrorizer\">{{cite magazine |url=http://swans.pair.com/PRESS/rev_STTerror.html |title=Swans: ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' |last=Terry |first=Nick |magazine=[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]] |accessdate=March 2, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111050138/http://swans.pair.com/PRESS/rev_STTerror.html |archivedate=January 11, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Soundtracks for the Blind'' has been met with acclaim by critics. ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' wrote that \"Swans' out-and-out noise may have receded into quietude and somnolent hypnoscapes, but this monster of an album will leave ripples pulsing out for many years to come.\"<ref name=\"Alternative Press\"/> Nick Terry of ''[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]'' magazine wrote, \"Gira has painstakingly recorded and produced this magnus [''sic''] opus with a ferocious attention to detail. Above all, it sounds phenomenal\".<ref name=\"Terrorizer\"/> The magazine later included it in their list of the \"100 Most Important Albums of the Nineties\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/terroris.htm#The%20Nineties|title=Rocklist.net....Terrorizer Magazine.....|website=www.rocklistmusic.co.uk|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIn a retrospective review, [[AllMusic]] critic Ned Raggett called ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' \"[Swans'] best album ever\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Raggett ranked the album at number 75 on his list of the best albums of the 1990s for ''[[Freaky Trigger]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.netcomuk.co.uk/~tewing/ned/n75.html |title=75. Swans \u2013 ''Soundtracks For The Blind'' |last=Raggett |first=Ned |work=[[Freaky Trigger]] |date=November 1999 |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040305065338/http://www.netcomuk.co.uk/~tewing/ned/n75.html |archivedate=March 5, 2004}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Disc One (Silver)\n| all_writing = [[Michael Gira]], unless noted\n| total_length = 72:06\n| title1 = Red Velvet Corridor\n| length1 = 3:04\n| title2 = I Was a Prisoner in Your Skull\n| length2 = 6:39\n| title3 = Helpless Child\n| length3 = 15:47\n| title4 = Live Through Me\n| length4 = 2:32\n| title5 = Yum-Yab Killers\n| writer5 = [[Jarboe]]\n| length5 = 5:07\n| title6 = The Beautiful Days\n| length6 = 7:49\n| title7 = Volcano\n| writer7 = Jarboe\n| length7 = 5:18\n| title8 = Mellothumb\n| length8 = 2:46\n| title9 = All Lined Up\n| length9 = 4:48\n| title10 = Surrogate 2\n| writer10 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length10 = 1:52\n| title11 = How They Suffer\n| length11 = 5:52\n| title12 = Animus\n| length12 = 10:41\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Disc Two (Copper)\n| title13 = Red Velvet Wound\n| writer13 = Jarboe\n| length13 = 2:02\n| title14 = The Sound\n| length14 = 13:11\n| title15 = Her Mouth Is Filled With Honey\n| writer15 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length15 = 3:19\n| title16 = Blood Section\n| length16 = 2:39\n| title17 = Hypogirl\n| length17 = 2:44\n| title18 = Minus Something\n| writer18 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length18 = 4:14\n| title19 = Empathy\n| length19 = 6:45\n| title20 = I Love You This Much\n| length20 = 7:23\n| title21 = YRP\n| length21 = 7:47\n| title22 = Fan's Lament\n| length22 = 1:28\n| title23 = Secret Friends\n| writer23 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length23 = 3:08\n| title24 = The Final Sacrifice\n| length24 = 10:27\n| title25 = YRP 2\n| length25 = 2:09\n| title26 = Surrogate Drone\n| length26 = 2:06\n| total_length = 69:31 \n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\nCredits for ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' adapted from liner notes.<ref>Track listing and credits as per liner notes for ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' album</ref>\n\n;Swans\n* [[Michael Gira]] - vocals, guitar, samples, sounds, loops, producer (all tracks except \"Volcano\")\n* [[Jarboe]] - vocals, sounds, loops, producer (on \"Volcano\")\n* [[Norman Westberg]] - additional musician\n* [[Algis Kizys]] - additional musician\n* [[Bill Rieflin]] - additional musician\n* Christoph Hahn - additional musician\n* Clinton Steele - additional musician\n* Larry Lame - additional musician, mixing and recording\n\n;Guest Musicians\n* Joe Goldring - electric guitar, bass guitar (on tracks 3, 5, 9, 12, 14, 19, 24, and 25)\n* [[Vudi]] - electric guitar, acoustic guitar (on tracks 3, 5, 9, 12, 14, 19, 24, and 25)\n* Larry Mullins - drums, percussion, vibraphone (on tracks 3, 5, 9, 12, 14, 19, 24, and 25)\n* Cris Force - viola (on \"Animus\" and \"YRP\")\n\n;Additional Personnel\n* Billy Anderson - mixing and recording\n* Chris Griffin - mixing, mastering and recording\n* Martin Bisi - mixing and recording\n* Andy Ray - live engineer on \"Yum-Yab Killers\", \"I Love You This Much\", \"The Final Sacrifice\" and \"YRP 2\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs master|8895}}\n\n{{Swans (band)}}\n\n[[Category:1996 albums]]\n[[Category:Atavistic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Swans (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Michael Gira]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jarboe]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Billy Anderson (producer)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Soundtracks for the Blind\n| type       = studio\n| longtype   = ([[double album]])\n| artist     = [[Swans (band)|Swans]]\n| cover      = Soundtracks for the Blind.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 22 October 1996\n| recorded   = 1981 \u2013 1996\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Experimental rock]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Isachs |title=Recorded Music: Swans, \u201cSoundtracks for the Blind\u201d (Young God, 1996) |url=https://blogs.colum.edu/reviewing-the-arts/2013/03/19/recorded-music-swans-soundtracks-for-the-blind-1996-young-god/ |website=Reviewing the Arts, Columbia College Chicago |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[post-rock]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=joshuatree |title=Swans - Soundtracks for the Blind |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/26462/Swans-Soundtracks-for-the-Blind/ |website=sputnikmusic |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[dark ambient]]\n*[[drone]]\n*[[avant-garde]]\n*[[post-industrial]]\n*[[neofolk|avant-folk]]\n*[[field recording]]\n*[[spoken word]]\n*[[sound collage]]\n}}\n| length     = 141:37\n| label      = [[Young God Records|Young God]]\n| producer   = [[Michael Gira]], [[Jarboe]] (track 7)\n| prev_title = [[Die T\u00fcr ist zu]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Swans Are Dead]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Soundtracks for the Blind\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Failure\" / \"Animus\n | single1date = 1996\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Soundtracks for the Blind''''' is the tenth studio album by [[Swans (band)|Swans]], and the last released until 2010's ''[[My Father Will Guide Me up a Rope to the Sky]]''. It was released as a [[Double album|double]] [[Compact disc|CD]] in 1996, through [[Young God Records]]. ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' was intended, as suggested by the title, to function as a sort of \"soundtrack for a non-existent film\", and is Swans' most varied studio effort.\n\nA [[reissue]] of the album was released on July 20, 2018, marking the first time ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' was released on [[Phonograph record|vinyl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://younggodrecords.com/products/soundtracks-2018|title=Soundtracks For The Blind (Remastered 2018) PREORDER|website=YOUNG GOD RECORDS|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nMuch of the album is tied together with audio collage works and sample-based textural pieces recorded at various times and places, as well as the use of previous Swans material (such as the lyrics of \"Your Property\" from ''[[Cop (album)|Cop]]'' for \"YRP\"). On this, frontman Michael Gira said in 1997:\n\n<blockquote>I've always been interested in different sounds like that and listened to [[Brian Eno]] and different kinds of music that use non-musical sources often, and as I made this record I had a lot of that material: those loops and things I'd made from '81; I had vocal loops that Jarboe had made in 1985 on a little sixteen second digital delay unit which was actually the first sampler... we had these tape narrations we'd been collecting, that she got from her father's desk when he was an FBI agent \u2013 surveillance tapes; I interviewed my father because I'm interested in his life, and took a little snippet of his experiences... then we had new things we'd recorded with our 'band' from the last tour; and some stuff we did for a soundtrack for a film. I threw all those into the computer and assembled it that way. So, in some things, there's something from 1981 playing simultaneously with something from '85 playing simultaneously with something from 1996. It's cross-faded and blended and mixed so to speak in the computer, cut-up and sometimes looped and reversed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://younggodrecords.com/press/98-swans/1426-swans-m-gira-interview |title=Swans <nowiki>| M. Gira |</nowiki> Interview |work=[[Young God Records|younggodrecords.com]] |access-date=March 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130210125055/http://younggodrecords.com/press/98-swans/1426-swans-m-gira-interview |archive-date=February 10, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn the Young God Records page for \"Soundtracks for the Blind\", Gira wrote this in 2008 about the general experience of making the album:\n\n<blockquote>This double CD album has everything in there \u2013 all the ideas from Swans\u2019 15 years of work. There\u2019s some contemporary recordings of the band as it existed in \u201896/7, with Larry Mullins on drums/percussion, Jarboe singing and playing keyboards, Vudi playing electric guitar, and Joe Goldring playing bass and electric guitar, and me singing and playing electric and acoustic guitar, but there\u2019s also a huge amount of sounds and recordings that I (and a few by Jarboe here too) collected over the years. These are reassembled, looped, mangled, and in many cases overdubbed upon to create new pieces of music. Being the \u201cartist\u201d in this case, it\u2019s hard for me to talk about this one, because the memory is so laden (or burdened!) with the experience of making this thing. I guess what I\u2019m trying to say here is I almost had a heart attack making it (slightly kidding here). It was just overwhelming. I really set my own trap, dug my own grave on this one. There was SO MUCH material to deal with, to sift through (whole trunks full of decomposing, moldy cassettes and discs with samples and sounds), and the task of making it into something coherent was at times debilitating. Really like climbing up a mountain of sand. I don\u2019t remember why I set this goal for myself, to somehow incorporate such a ridiculously disparate amount of material. I think maybe it was so I could justify throwing all that crap into the local dump, which is what I did when I finished the album. But in the end, after centuries of picking at this huge iceberg of material with a toothpick, my trusty engineer Chris Griffin and I managed to sculpt something out of it. It actually breathes, seems to live, in most places I think. There\u2019s a press release below written by Kurt at Atavistic (Swans label at the time), and some reviews too, which might give you a better idea of how this sounds. Anyway, in the end, I was elated with this music, both because I liked it and because finishing it meant I could finally lay Swans to rest after 15 years. In my case, I\u2019m always happiest when I\u2019m leaving.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://younggodrecords.com/collections/swans/products/soundtracks-for-the-blind |title=Soundtracks for the Blind <nowiki>| M. Gira |</nowiki> Interview |work=[[Young God Records|younggodrecords.com]] |access-date=November 28, 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/HaRzt |archive-date=July 13, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/soundtracks-for-the-blind-mw0000080044 |title=''Soundtracks for the Blind'' \u2013 Swans |last=Raggett |first=Ned |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=March 2, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2score = 5/5<ref name=\"Alternative Press\">{{cite magazine |title=Swans: ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' |magazine=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |issue=103 |date=February 1997 |page=55}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[MusicHound|MusicHound Rock]]''\n| rev3score = 4/5<ref>''MusicHound Rock: The Essential Album Guide'' (1996)</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev4score = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/26462/Swans-Soundtracks-for-the-Blind/ |title=Swans \u2013 ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' |author=joshuatree |work=[[Sputnikmusic]] |date=July 26, 2008 |accessdate=March 2, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Terrorizer\">{{cite magazine |url=http://swans.pair.com/PRESS/rev_STTerror.html |title=Swans: ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' |last=Terry |first=Nick |magazine=[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]] |accessdate=March 2, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111050138/http://swans.pair.com/PRESS/rev_STTerror.html |archivedate=January 11, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Soundtracks for the Blind'' has been met with acclaim by critics. ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' wrote that \"Swans' out-and-out noise may have receded into quietude and somnolent hypnoscapes, but this monster of an album will leave ripples pulsing out for many years to come.\"<ref name=\"Alternative Press\"/> Nick Terry of ''[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]'' magazine wrote, \"Gira has painstakingly recorded and produced this magnus [''sic''] opus with a ferocious attention to detail. Above all, it sounds phenomenal\".<ref name=\"Terrorizer\"/> The magazine later included it in their list of the \"100 Most Important Albums of the Nineties\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/terroris.htm#The%20Nineties|title=Rocklist.net....Terrorizer Magazine.....|website=www.rocklistmusic.co.uk|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIn a retrospective review, [[AllMusic]] critic Ned Raggett called ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' \"[Swans'] best album ever\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Raggett ranked the album at number 75 on his list of the best albums of the 1990s for ''[[Freaky Trigger]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.netcomuk.co.uk/~tewing/ned/n75.html |title=75. Swans \u2013 ''Soundtracks For The Blind'' |last=Raggett |first=Ned |work=[[Freaky Trigger]] |date=November 1999 |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040305065338/http://www.netcomuk.co.uk/~tewing/ned/n75.html |archivedate=March 5, 2004}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Disc One (Silver)\n| all_writing = [[Michael Gira]], unless noted\n| total_length = 72:06\n| title1 = Red Velvet Corridor\n| length1 = 3:04\n| title2 = I Was a Prisoner in Your Skull\n| length2 = 6:39\n| title3 = Helpless Child\n| length3 = 15:47\n| title4 = Live Through Me\n| length4 = 2:32\n| title5 = Yum-Yab Killers\n| writer5 = [[Jarboe]]\n| length5 = 5:07\n| title6 = The Beautiful Days\n| length6 = 7:49\n| title7 = Volcano\n| writer7 = Jarboe\n| length7 = 5:18\n| title8 = Mellothumb\n| length8 = 2:46\n| title9 = All Lined Up\n| length9 = 4:48\n| title10 = Surrogate 2\n| writer10 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length10 = 1:52\n| title11 = How They Suffer\n| length11 = 5:52\n| title12 = Animus\n| length12 = 10:41\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Disc Two (Copper)\n| title13 = Red Velvet Wound\n| writer13 = Jarboe\n| length13 = 2:02\n| title14 = The Sound\n| length14 = 13:11\n| title15 = Her Mouth Is Filled With Honey\n| writer15 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length15 = 3:19\n| title16 = Blood Section\n| length16 = 2:39\n| title17 = Hypogirl\n| length17 = 2:44\n| title18 = Minus Something\n| writer18 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length18 = 4:14\n| title19 = Empathy\n| length19 = 6:45\n| title20 = I Love You This Much\n| length20 = 7:23\n| title21 = YRP\n| length21 = 7:47\n| title22 = Fan's Lament\n| length22 = 1:28\n| title23 = Secret Friends\n| writer23 = Gira, Jarboe\n| length23 = 3:08\n| title24 = The Final Sacrifice\n| length24 = 10:27\n| title25 = YRP 2\n| length25 = 2:09\n| title26 = Surrogate Drone\n| length26 = 2:06\n| total_length = 69:31 \n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\nCredits for ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' adapted from liner notes.<ref>Track listing and credits as per liner notes for ''Soundtracks for the Blind'' album</ref>\n\n;Swans\n* [[Michael Gira]] - vocals, guitar, samples, sounds, loops, producer (all tracks except \"Volcano\")\n* [[Jarboe]] - vocals, sounds, loops, producer (on \"Volcano\")\n* [[Norman Westberg]] - additional musician\n* [[Algis Kizys]] - additional musician\n* [[Bill Rieflin]] - additional musician\n* Christoph Hahn - additional musician\n* Clinton Steele - additional musician\n* Larry Lame - additional musician, mixing and recording\n\n;Guest Musicians\n* Joe Goldring - electric guitar, bass guitar (on tracks 3, 5, 9, 12, 14, 19, 24, and 25)\n* [[Vudi]] - electric guitar, acoustic guitar (on tracks 3, 5, 9, 12, 14, 19, 24, and 25)\n* Larry Mullins - drums, percussion, vibraphone (on tracks 3, 5, 9, 12, 14, 19, 24, and 25)\n* Cris Force - viola (on \"Animus\" and \"YRP\")\n\n;Additional Personnel\n* Billy Anderson - mixing and recording\n* Chris Griffin - mixing, mastering and recording\n* Martin Bisi - mixing and recording\n* Andy Ray - live engineer on \"Yum-Yab Killers\", \"I Love You This Much\", \"The Final Sacrifice\" and \"YRP 2\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs master|8895}}\n\n{{Swans (band)}}\n\n[[Category:1996 albums]]\n[[Category:Atavistic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Swans (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produc