{"title_page": "Simon Neil", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Simon Neil\n| image               = 13-06-07 RaR Biffy Clyro Simon Neil 02.jpg\n| caption             = Neil at Rock am Ring 2013\n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Simon Alexander Neil\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=y|1979|8|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]], Scotland\n| death_date          =\n| origin              = Irvine, North Ayrshire, Scotland\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar\n| genre               = [[Alternative rock]], [[post-hardcore]]\n| occupation          = Singer, songwriter, record producer\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Beggars Banquet Records|Beggars Banquet]]<br />14th Floor<br />[[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Biffy Clyro]]<br />[[Marmaduke Duke]] <br /> ZZC\n| website             = [http://www.biffyclyro.com/ www.biffyclyro.com]\n| current_members     =\n| past_members        =\n}}\n'''Simon Alexander Neil''' (born 31 August 1979) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] vocalist, guitarist, and songwriter.\n\nHe is known for his work in the bands [[Biffy Clyro]] and [[Marmaduke Duke]].\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Biffy Clyro ===\n[[File:14-08-08 Taubertal Biffy Clyro Simon Neil 2.JPG|thumb|14-08-08 Taubertal Biffy Clyro Simon Neil 2]]\n{{Main|Biffy Clyro}}\nBorn in [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]], Simon Neil formed Biffy Clyro in 1995 at 15 years old recruiting [[Kilmarnock]]-born [[James Johnston (Scottish musician)|James Johnston]] and someone known only as Barry on bass and drums respectively, calling themselves Skrewfish.<ref name=Beggars.bio>[http://www.beggars.com/us/biffyclyro/index.html Biffy Clyro Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070408171826/http://www.beggars.com/us/biffyclyro/index.html |date=8 April 2007 }} on [[Beggar's Banquet Records|Beggar's Banquet USA]]</ref> Barry was soon replaced by [[Ben Johnston (Scottish musician)|Ben Johnston]], James's twin brother, and Biffy Clyro was effectively formed. In 1997, the trio moved to [[Glasgow]], where Neil studied Electronics with Music at the [[University of Glasgow]]. He also Studied Film and TV for a year before leaving to pursue music full-time. By then, Simon's musical tastes had expanded; In 2000, the band were spotted at the Unsigned Bands stage at [[T in the Park]] by a [[Beggars Banquet Records|Beggars Banquet]] representative. Soon after, the band was signed to the [[Independent record label|independent]] Beggar's Banquet.\n\nBiffy Clyro have since released seven albums, signed to a major record label, and toured relentlessly. Neil has stated that Biffy Clyro lyrics often come from phrases he writes down in a notebook he keeps by his bed.\n\n=== Marmaduke Duke ===\n{{Main|Marmaduke Duke}}\nNeil plays with JP Reid of fellow Ayrshire group [[Sucioperro]] in [[Marmaduke Duke]], under the pseudonym \"The Atmosphere\", which released their first album, ''[[The Magnificent Duke]]'', in 2005.\n\nIt was announced in late 2008 that the Duke was to make a return in 2009 with the follow-up album and second in the trilogy, ''[[Duke Pandemonium]]''.  The first single from the second album, \"Kid Gloves\" was released on 9 February 2009.\n\n=== Solo career ===\n\nNeil performs under the name ZZC. His debut single, \"To the Bone\", was used in the [[BBC]]'s \u2018[[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]] Rescores: [[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]] (curated by [[Zane Lowe]])\u2019 project.\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Simon neil.jpg|thumb|Simon Neil]]\nNeil lives in [[Ayr]] with his wife Francesca, whom he married at St. Columba Church in Ayr on 5 January 2008. The song \"[[God Only Knows]]\" by [[The Beach Boys]] was used for their first dance, and Neil has the song's chorus, \"God only knows what I'd be without you\", tattooed on his chest.<ref name=\"sweet_music\">''Ayshire Post'', 9 January 2008, [http://www.ayrshirepost.net/tm_headline=sweet-music&method=full&objectid=20331401&siteid=73592-name_page.html Sweet music]</ref>. Neil is a lifelong fan of the football team [[Rangers FC]].<ref>BBC Sport, 5 May 2014, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27240312]</ref>\n\n== Musical equipment used ==\nThe following is a list of musical equipment used by Simon Neil:\n\n=== Guitars ===\n''Electric''\n* [[Fender Stratocaster|Fender Standard Stratocasters]]<ref name=BiffyTabs>[http://www.biffytabs.biffierthanthou.com/e_si.htm BiffyTabs Equipment \u2013 Simon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007202112/http://www.biffytabs.biffierthanthou.com/e_si.htm |date=7 October 2007 }}</ref> \u2013 Various different Mexican models, including White, Red, Sunburst (with neck pickup & controls removed), Black, and Metallic Blue.\n* [[Fender Stratocaster|Fender 1960 Custom Shop Stratocasters]]<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013 Fiesta Red, Frost Metallic, Lake Placid Blue, and White.\n* [[Fender Stratocaster|Fender 50s Stratocaster Relic]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Fender Telecaster]] Standard<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013  USA model, owned by James Johnston, three tone sunburst, can be seen in the music video for \"[[Living is a Problem Because Everything Dies]]\".\n* [[Fender Telecaster]] '62 Custom<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013 Japanese model, three tone sunburst, can be seen in the music video for \"Only One Word Comes to Mind\".\n* [[Fender Telecaster Custom]] 1972 reissue, black. Can be seen in the music video for \"Mountains\".\n* [[Squier Stratocaster|Squier Simon Neil Signature Stratocaster]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Patrick Eggle]] New York<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013 Red.\n* [[Gretsch White Falcon]] Used live for the song \"Diary of Always\" and is seen in the music video for \"[[Folding Stars]]\"\n* [[Gibson ES-335]] \u2013 used live for \"God & Satan\"\n* [[Gretsch G2420T]] \u2013 used for music video of \"Howl\".\n\n=== Effects pedals ===\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS TU-2 Chromatic Tuner]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS MD-2 Distortion]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS MT-2 Metal Zone]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS DD-6 Digital Delay]] x2<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS LS-2 Line Selector]]<ref name=UberProAudio>{{cite web|url=http://www.uberproaudio.com/content/view/530/38/|title=Biffy Clyro \u2013 Simon Neil Guitar Rig Gear and Equipment|work=uberproaudio.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007012335/http://www.uberproaudio.com/content/view/530/38/|archivedate=7 October 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Origin Effects Cali76 Compressor]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n\n=== Previous effects pedals ===\n* [[BOSS DS-1]] Distortion<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS HM-2 Heavy Metal]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Dunlop Cry Baby]] Wah Wah<ref name=\"UberProAudio\" />\n* [[Electro Harmonix]] Micro POG<ref name=\"UberProAudio\" />\n\n=== Amplifiers ===\n* [[Peavey Electronics|Peavey Delta Blues Combo]]<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender Hot Rod Deville 4x10 Combo]]\n* [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall 1959SLP Head]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Peavey Electronics|Peavey Classic Head]]<ref name=BiffyTabs /> and Peavey Classic 412 Cabinet<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Hayden (electronics company)|Hayden MoFo 30W tube head with Hayden 4x12]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Fender Super Sonic 100 BLK Head]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Kemper Profiling Amplifier PowerHead]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n\n==Discography==\n===Biffy Clyro===\n{{Main|Biffy Clyro discography}}\n* ''[[Blackened Sky]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[The Vertigo of Bliss]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Infinity Land]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Puzzle (Biffy Clyro album)|Puzzle]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Only Revolutions (album)|Only Revolutions]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Opposites (album)|Opposites]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Ellipsis (Biffy Clyro album)|Ellipsis]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[MTV Unplugged: Live at Roundhouse, London|MTV Unplugged (Live at the Roundhouse, London)]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]'' (2019)\n\n===Marmaduke Duke===\n* ''[[The Magnificent Duke]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Duke Pandemonium]]'' (2009)\n\n===Other appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=10| Year \n!width=280| Song \n!width=100| Artist \n!width=280| Album\n|-\n|2001\n|\"Zionist Timing\"\n|[[Aereogramme (band)|Aereogramme]]\n|[[A Story in White]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2002\n|\"Hangover\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Sucioperro]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Why Bliss Destroy]]''\n|-\n|\"Love in the Guise of Friendship\"\n|-\n|\"Capable of More\"\n|-\n|2009\n|\"Graves\"\n|[[Gallows (band)|Gallows]]\n|''[[Grey Britain]]''\n|-\n|2010\n|\"It's My Tail and I'll Chase It If I Want To\"\n|[[Oceansize]]\n|''[[Self Preserved While the Bodies Float Up]]''\n|-\n|2014\n|\"Sun Riders\"\n|Krokodil\n|''Nachash''\n|-\n|2016\n|\"Reason to Stay\"\n|[[Good Charlotte]]\n|''[[Youth Authority]]''\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category|Simon Neil}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Marmaduke Duke}}\n{{Biffy Clyro}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neil, Simon}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Biffy Clyro members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Prestwick Academy]]\n[[Category:People from Ayr]]\n[[Category:People from Irvine, North Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Scottish male singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Simon Neil\n| image               = 13-06-07 RaR Biffy Clyro Simon Neil 02.jpg\n| caption             = Neil at Rock am Ring 2013\n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Simon Alexander Neil\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=y|1979|8|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]], Scotland\n| death_date          =\n| origin              = Irvine, North Ayrshire, Scotland\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar\n| genre               = [[Alternative rock]], [[post-hardcore]]\n| occupation          = Singer, songwriter, record producer\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Beggars Banquet Records|Beggars Banquet]]<br />14th Floor<br />[[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Biffy Clyro]]<br />[[Marmaduke Duke]] <br /> ZZC\n| website             = [http://www.biffyclyro.com/ www.biffyclyro.com]\n| current_members     =\n| past_members        =\n}}\n'''Simon Alexander Neil''' (born 31 August 1979) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] vocalist, guitarist, and songwriter.\n\nHe is known for his work in the bands [[Biffy Clyro]] and [[Marmaduke Duke]].\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Biffy Clyro ===\n[[File:14-08-08 Taubertal Biffy Clyro Simon Neil 2.JPG|thumb|14-08-08 Taubertal Biffy Clyro Simon Neil 2]]\n{{Main|Biffy Clyro}}\nBorn in [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]], Simon Neil formed Biffy Clyro in 1995 at 15 years old recruiting [[Kilmarnock]]-born [[James Johnston (Scottish musician)|James Johnston]] and someone known only as Barry on bass and drums respectively, calling themselves Skrewfish.<ref name=Beggars.bio>[http://www.beggars.com/us/biffyclyro/index.html Biffy Clyro Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070408171826/http://www.beggars.com/us/biffyclyro/index.html |date=8 April 2007 }} on [[Beggar's Banquet Records|Beggar's Banquet USA]]</ref> Barry was soon replaced by [[Ben Johnston (Scottish musician)|Ben Johnston]], James's twin brother, and Biffy Clyro was effectively formed. In 1997, the trio moved to [[Glasgow]], where Neil studied Electronics with Music at the [[University of Glasgow]]. He also Studied Film and TV for a year before leaving to pursue music full-time. By then, Simon's musical tastes had expanded; In 2000, the band were spotted at the Unsigned Bands stage at [[T in the Park]] by a [[Beggars Banquet Records|Beggars Banquet]] representative. Soon after, the band was signed to the [[Independent record label|independent]] Beggar's Banquet.\n\nBiffy Clyro have since released seven albums, signed to a major record label, and toured relentlessly. Neil has stated that Biffy Clyro lyrics often come from phrases he writes down in a notebook he keeps by his bed.\n\n=== Marmaduke Duke ===\n{{Main|Marmaduke Duke}}\nNeil plays with JP Reid of fellow Ayrshire group [[Sucioperro]] in [[Marmaduke Duke]], under the pseudonym \"The Atmosphere\", which released their first album, ''[[The Magnificent Duke]]'', in 2005.\n\nIt was announced in late 2008 that the Duke was to make a return in 2009 with the follow-up album and second in the trilogy, ''[[Duke Pandemonium]]''.  The first single from the second album, \"Kid Gloves\" was released on 9 February 2009.\n\n=== Solo career ===\n\nNeil performs under the name ZZC. His debut single, \"To the Bone\", was used in the [[BBC]]'s \u2018[[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]] Rescores: [[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]] (curated by [[Zane Lowe]])\u2019 project.\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Simon neil.jpg|thumb|Simon Neil]]\nNeil lives in [[Ayr]] with his wife Francesca, whom he married at St. Columba Church in Ayr on 5 January 2008. The song \"[[God Only Knows]]\" by [[The Beach Boys]] was used for their first dance, and Neil has the song's chorus, \"God only knows what I'd be without you\", tattooed on his chest.<ref name=\"sweet_music\">''Ayshire Post'', 9 January 2008, [http://www.ayrshirepost.net/tm_headline=sweet-music&method=full&objectid=20331401&siteid=73592-name_page.html Sweet music]</ref>. Neil is a lifelong fan of the football team [[Rangers FC]].<ref>BBC Sport, 5 May 2014, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27240312]</ref>\n\n== Musical equipment used ==\nThe following is a list of musical equipment used by Simon Neil:\n\n=== Guitars ===\n''Electric''\n* [[Fender Stratocaster|Fender Standard Stratocasters]]<ref name=BiffyTabs>[http://www.biffytabs.biffierthanthou.com/e_si.htm BiffyTabs Equipment \u2013 Simon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007202112/http://www.biffytabs.biffierthanthou.com/e_si.htm |date=7 October 2007 }}</ref> \u2013 Various different Mexican models, including White, Red, Sunburst (with neck pickup & controls removed), Black, and Metallic Blue.\n* [[Fender Stratocaster|Fender 1960 Custom Shop Stratocasters]]<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013 Fiesta Red, Frost Metallic, Lake Placid Blue, and White.\n* [[Fender Stratocaster|Fender 50s Stratocaster Relic]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Fender Telecaster]] Standard<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013  USA model, owned by James Johnston, three tone sunburst, can be seen in the music video for \"[[Living is a Problem Because Everything Dies]]\".\n* [[Fender Telecaster]] '62 Custom<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013 Japanese model, three tone sunburst, can be seen in the music video for \"Only One Word Comes to Mind\".\n* [[Fender Telecaster Custom]] 1972 reissue, black. Can be seen in the music video for \"Mountains\".\n* [[Squier Stratocaster|Squier Simon Neil Signature Stratocaster]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Patrick Eggle]] New York<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \u2013 Red.\n* [[Gretsch White Falcon]] Used live for the song \"Diary of Always\" and is seen in the music video for \"[[Folding Stars]]\"\n* [[Gibson ES-335]] \u2013 used live for \"God & Satan\"\n* [[Gretsch G2420T]] \u2013 used for music video of \"Howl\".\n\n=== Effects pedals ===\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS TU-2 Chromatic Tuner]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS MD-2 Distortion]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS MT-2 Metal Zone]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS DD-6 Digital Delay]] x2<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS LS-2 Line Selector]]<ref name=UberProAudio>{{cite web|url=http://www.uberproaudio.com/content/view/530/38/|title=Biffy Clyro \u2013 Simon Neil Guitar Rig Gear and Equipment|work=uberproaudio.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007012335/http://www.uberproaudio.com/content/view/530/38/|archivedate=7 October 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Origin Effects Cali76 Compressor]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n\n=== Previous effects pedals ===\n* [[BOSS DS-1]] Distortion<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Boss Corporation|BOSS HM-2 Heavy Metal]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Dunlop Cry Baby]] Wah Wah<ref name=\"UberProAudio\" />\n* [[Electro Harmonix]] Micro POG<ref name=\"UberProAudio\" />\n\n=== Amplifiers ===\n* [[Peavey Electronics|Peavey Delta Blues Combo]]<ref name=BiffyTabs /> \n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender Hot Rod Deville 4x10 Combo]]\n* [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall 1959SLP Head]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Peavey Electronics|Peavey Classic Head]]<ref name=BiffyTabs /> and Peavey Classic 412 Cabinet<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Hayden (electronics company)|Hayden MoFo 30W tube head with Hayden 4x12]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Fender Super Sonic 100 BLK Head]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n* [[Kemper Profiling Amplifier PowerHead]]<ref name=BiffyTabs />\n\n==Discography==\n===Biffy Clyro===\n{{Main|Biffy Clyro discography}}\n* ''[[Blackened Sky]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[The Vertigo of Bliss]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Infinity Land]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Puzzle (Biffy Clyro album)|Puzzle]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Only Revolutions (album)|Only Revolutions]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Opposites (album)|Opposites]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Ellipsis (Biffy Clyro album)|Ellipsis]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[MTV Unplugged (Live at the Roundhouse, London)]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]'' (2019)\n\n===Marmaduke Duke===\n* ''[[The Magnificent Duke]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Duke Pandemonium]]'' (2009)\n\n===Other appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=10| Year \n!width=280| Song \n!width=100| Artist \n!width=280| Album\n|-\n|2001\n|\"Zionist Timing\"\n|[[Aereogramme (band)|Aereogramme]]\n|[[A Story in White]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2002\n|\"Hangover\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Sucioperro]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Why Bliss Destroy]]''\n|-\n|\"Love in the Guise of Friendship\"\n|-\n|\"Capable of More\"\n|-\n|2009\n|\"Graves\"\n|[[Gallows (band)|Gallows]]\n|''[[Grey Britain]]''\n|-\n|2010\n|\"It's My Tail and I'll Chase It If I Want To\"\n|[[Oceansize]]\n|''[[Self Preserved While the Bodies Float Up]]''\n|-\n|2014\n|\"Sun Riders\"\n|Krokodil\n|''Nachash''\n|-\n|2016\n|\"Reason to Stay\"\n|[[Good Charlotte]]\n|''[[Youth Authority]]''\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category|Simon Neil}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Marmaduke Duke}}\n{{Biffy Clyro}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neil, Simon}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Biffy Clyro members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Prestwick Academy]]\n[[Category:People from Ayr]]\n[[Category:People from Irvine, North Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Scottish male singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n", "name_user": "J\u00e2\u010d\u00f4b.x.x.x", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiffy Clyro", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Neil"}
{"title_page": "Bernardine Evaristo", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image         = Bernadine Evaristo.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| name          = Bernardine Evaristo\n|honorific_suffix =[[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]] [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]], [[English Association|FEA]]\n| caption       = Evaristo in 2008\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1959}}\n| birth_place   = [[London]], England, UK\n| birth_name    = Bernardine Anne Mobolaji Evaristo\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    = Novelist, critic, poet, playwright, academic\n| education     = [[Eltham Hill Grammar School|Eltham Hill Grammar School for Girls]]; [[Rose Bruford College of Speech and Drama]]; [[Goldsmiths College, University of London]]\n| nationality   = British\n| notable works =''[[Lara (novel)|Lara]]'' (1997)<br> ''[[The Emperor's Babe]]'' (2001)<br>''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'' (2019)\n| awards        = [[Booker Prize]], [[2019 Man Booker Prize|2019]]\n| website       = {{URL|https://bevaristo.com/}}\n}}\n'''Bernardine Evaristo''', [[Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]] [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]], [[English Association|FEA]] (born 1959), is a British author of eight works of fiction. Her bestselling novel, ''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'',<ref>[https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/311/311140/girl--woman--other/9780241364901.html ''Girl, Woman, Other''], Penguin.</ref> won the [[Man Booker Prize|Booker Prize]] in 2019. It was also one of Barack Obama's 19 Favourite Books of 2019. Evaristo's writing also includes short fiction, drama, poetry, essays, literary criticism, and projects for stage and radio. Two of her books, ''[[The Emperor's Babe]]'' (2001) and ''[[Hello Mum]]'' (2010), have been adapted into [[BBC Radio 4]] dramas. She is currently Professor of Creative Writing at [[Brunel University|Brunel University London]]<ref name=\"Brunel\">[http://www.brunel.ac.uk/people/bernardine-evaristo \"Bernardine Evaristo, Professor of Creative Writing\"], Brunel University London.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/sep/08/bernardine-evaristo-cultural-highlights|title=On My Radar: Bernadine Evaristo's cultural highlights|first=Ellie |last=Bothwell|date=8 September 2013|accessdate=9 September 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> and the vice-chair of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref>[https://rsliterature.org/about-us/council/ \"Council\"], The Royal Society of Literature. Retrieved 28 July 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Sethi\">{{cite news|last=Sethi|first=Anita|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/27/bernardine-evaristo-girl-woman-other-interview|title=Bernardine Evaristo: 'I want to put presence into absence'|work=The Guardian|date=27 April 2019|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nEvaristo is a longstanding advocate for the inclusion of writers and artists of colour. She founded the [[Brunel University African Poetry Prize]]<ref>[http://www.africanpoetryprize.org/ Brunel International African Poetry Prize] website.</ref> in 2012 and The Complete Works poets development scheme (2007\u20132017).<ref name=TCW>{{Cite web |url=https://thecompleteworkspoetry.com/ |title=The Complete Works |access-date=15 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216025030/https://thecompleteworkspoetry.com/ |archive-date=16 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She co-founded Spread the Word writer development agency<ref>[https://www.spreadtheword.org.uk/ \"About Us\"], Spread the Word.</ref> (1995\u2013present) and, in the 1980s, Britain's first black women's theatre company, [[Theatre of Black Women]].<ref name=UH>[https://www.unfinishedhistories.com/history/companies/theatre-of-black-women/ \"Theatre of Black Women\"], Unfinished Histories: Recording the History of Alternative Theatre. Retrieved 29 July 2019.</ref> She also organised Britain's first major black theatre conference, Future Histories, for the Black Theatre Forum,<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/companies/black-theatre-forum Black Theatre Forum]</ref> in 1995 in the [[Royal Festival Hall]], and Britain's first major conference on black British writing, ''Tracing Paper'', in 1997, at the [[Museum of London]].\n\n==Biography==\nEvaristo was born in [[Eltham]], south-east [[London]], and christened Bernardine Anne Mobolaji Evaristo.<ref>Harolds, Laolu (7 September 2019), [https://tribuneonlineng.com/two-nigerian-novelists-make-2019-booker-prize-shortlist/ \"Two Nigerian Novelists Make 2019 Booker Prize Shortlist\"], ''Nigerian Tribune''.</ref> She was raised in [[Woolwich]]. She is the fourth of eight children born to her white English mother, who was a schoolteacher, and her [[Nigerian]] father, who migrated to Britain in 1949 and became a welder and local [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] councillor.<ref name=\"Official website\">[http://bevaristo.com/ \"Bio\"], Author's website.</ref> Her paternal grandfather was a [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] Aguda or [[Saro (Nigeria)|Saro]] who returned from [[Brazil]] to Nigeria, and her paternal grandmother was from [[Abeokuta]] in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genevieveng.com/bernadine-evaristo-on-the-crossroads-of-culture/|title=Social: Bernadine Evaristo \u2026on the crossroads of culture|first=AdeOla |last=Fadumiye|website=Genevieve|accessdate=9 September 2014|url-status=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911003701/http://www.genevieveng.com/bernadine-evaristo-on-the-crossroads-of-culture/|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3591629/A-writers-life-Bernadine-Evaristo.html|title=A Writer's Life: Bernadine Evaristo|newspaper=The Telegraph|location=United Kingdom|date=23 March 2003|first=Tom |last=Payne|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Cambridge Introduction to Postcolonial Literatures in English|publisher =Cambridge University Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgeintrodu0000inne/page/68 68]|first=C. L. |last=Innes|isbn=978-1139-4655-95|accessdate=9 September 2014|url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgeintrodu0000inne|url-access=registration|quote=Bernardine Evaristo grandfather slave.|year=2007}}</ref> Her mother's paternal great-grandfather arrived in London from Germany in the 1860s and settled in Woolwich, south-east London, and her mother's maternal grandmother arrived in London from [[Ireland]] in the 1880s and settled in [[Islington]].<ref name=\"British Council\">[https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/bernardine-evaristo Bernardine Evaristo biography], British Council, Literature.</ref> Evaristo was educated at Greenwich Young People's Theatre (now the Tramshed, in Woolwich), [[Eltham Hill Grammar School|Eltham Hill Grammar School for Girls]], the [[Rose Bruford College of Speech and Drama]] and [[Goldsmiths College, University of London]], from where she received her doctorate in creative writing in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gold.ac.uk/our-people/profile-hub/english-and-comparative-literature/pg/other/bernardine-evaristo/|title=Bernardine Evaristo, Goldsmiths College|last= |first= |date= |website=gold.ac.uk|publisher=Goldsmiths University of London|access-date=16 October 2019|quote=}}</ref> In 2019 she was appointed Woolwich Laureate by the [[Greenwich+Docklands International Festival|Greenwich and Docklands International Festival]], reconnecting to and writing about the home town she left when she was 18.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/sep/07/bernardine-evaristo-made-in-woolwich|title=Bernardine Evaristo on Woolwich: 'We weren\u2019t allowed to play outside'|last= |first= |date=7 September 2019|website=theguardian.com|publisher=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=16 October 2019|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Writer and editor==\nEvaristo is the author of eight books of fiction and verse fiction that explore aspects of the [[African diaspora]].<ref name=Brunel/> She notably experiments with form and narrative perspective,<ref name=Brunel /> often merging the past with the present, fiction with poetry, the factual with the speculative, and reality with alternate realities (as in her 2008 novel ''[[Blonde Roots]]'').<ref>Merritt, Stephanie (24 August 2008), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/aug/24/fiction \"When slavery isn't such a black-and-white issue\"], ''The Observer''.</ref> Her verse novel ''The Emperor's Babe'' (Penguin, 2001) is about a black teenage girl whose parents are from [[Nubia]], who comes of age in Roman London nearly two thousand years ago.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} It won an [[Arts Council England|Arts Council]] Writers Award 2000; a [[Nesta (charity)|NESTA]] Fellowship Award in 2003; it was chosen by ''[[The Times]]'' as one of the \"100 Best Books of the Decade\" in 2010;<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-100-best-books-of-the-decade-952h76nd689 \"The 100 Best Books of the Decade\"], ''The Times'', 14 November 2009/</ref> and it was adapted into a [[BBC Radio 4]] play in 2013.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01sjjy3 ''The Emperor's Babe''], BBC Radio 4, 23 May 2013.</ref> Next she published ''[[Soul Tourists]]'' (Penguin, 2005), about a mismatched couple driving across Europe to the Middle East, which featured ghosts of real figures of colour from European history.<ref>[http://www.transculturalwriting.com/radiophonics/contents/writersonwriting/bernardineevaristo/soultourists-analysis/index.html \"Extract from ''Soul Tourists'' \u2014 Analysis\"], Crossing Borders.</ref><ref>Adams, Sarah (16 July 2005), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/jul/16/featuresreviews.guardianreview22 \"What a trip\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref>\n\nHer novel ''Blonde Roots'' (Penguin, 2008) is a satire that inverts the history of the [[transatlantic slave trade]] and replaces it with a universe where Africans enslave Europeans.<ref>[[Ron Charles (critic)|Charles, Ron]], [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/16/AR2009011600381.html \"Race Reversal\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 18 January 2009.</ref> ''Blonde Roots'' won the Orange Youth Panel Award and Big Red Read Award.<ref name=\"British Council\"/> Evaristo's other books include the verse novel ''[[Lara (novel)|Lara]]'' ([[Bloodaxe Books]], 2009, with an earlier version published in 1997), which fictionalised the multiple cultural strands of her family history going back over 150 years as well as her mixed-race London childhood.<ref>[http://www.bloodaxebooks.com/ecs/product/lara-927 Bernardine Evaristo, ''Lara''] at Bloodaxe Books.</ref> This won the [[Ethnic Multicultural Media Academy|EMMA Best Novel Award]] in 1998.<ref name=\"British Council\" /> Her novella ''Hello Mum'' (Penguin, 2010) was chosen as \"The Big Read\" for the [[County of Suffolk]], and adapted into a BBC Radio 4 play in 2012.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01l8rbj \"Hello Mum\"], ''Afternoon Drama'', BBC Radio 4, 3 August 2012.</ref>\n\nAs an editor, she guest-edited the September 2014 issue of ''[[Mslexia]]'' magazine, the [[Poetry Society|Poetry Society of Great Britain]]'s centenary winter issue of ''[[Poetry Review]]'' (2012), titled \"Offending Frequencies\"; a special issue of ''[[Wasafiri]]'' magazine called ''[[Black British|Black Britain]]: Beyond Definition'' (Routledge, 2010), with poet Karen McCarthy-Woolf; ''Ten'',<ref>[http://www.poetrybooks.co.uk/poetry_portal/ten_new_poets \"Ten New Poets by Bernardine Evaristo\"], Poetry Book Society. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426215058/http://www.poetrybooks.co.uk/poetry_portal/ten_new_poets |date=26 April 2014 }}.</ref> an anthology of Black and Asian poets, with poet [[Daljit Nagra]] (Bloodaxe Books, 2010) and in 2007, she co-edited the New Writing Anthology ''NW15'' ([[Granta]]/[[British Council]]). She was also editor of ''FrontSeat'' intercultural magazine in the 1990s,<ref name=\"Diaspora\">[http://www.bbawriting.com/bernardine-evaristo/ \"Bernardine Evaristo\"] at Diaspora Writers UK. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427023247/http://www.bbawriting.com/bernardine-evaristo/ |date=27 April 2016 }}.</ref> and one of the editors of ''Black Women Talk Poetry'' anthology (published in 1987 by the Black Womantalk Poetry collective of which Evaristo was part),<ref>Evaristo, Bernardine (19 October 2019), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/oct/19/bernadine-evaristo-what-a-time-to-be-a-black-british-womxn-writer \"Bernardine Evaristo: 'These are unprecedented times for black female writers'\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref> Britain's first such substantial anthology, featuring among its 20 poets [[Jackie Kay]], [[Dorothea Smartt]] and [[Adjoa Andoh]].<ref>Osborne, Deirdre (ed.) (2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=f48wDQAAQBAJ&pg=PR17&lpg=PR17&dq=%22%27Black+Women+Talk+Poetry%22+first+anthology&source=bl&ots=2mTjw3UiOF&sig=ACfU3U1D3ipRTXKvAC0ln3l5MKPXiagN0Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwito6rV8pbmAhUxTxUIHRDoDokQ6AEwA3oECC8QAQ#v=onepage&q=%22'Black%20Women%20Talk%20Poetry%22&f=false ''The Cambridge Companion to British Black and Asian Literature (1945\u20132010)''], Cambridge University Press, p. xvii.</ref>\n\nHer 2014 novel was ''Mr Loverman'' ([[Penguin Books|Penguin]] UK, 2013/ [[Akashic Books]] USA, 2014), about a septuagenarian Caribbean Londoner who is a [[closet homosexual]] and considering his options after a 50-year marriage to his wife.<ref>[[Maggie Gee (novelist)|Gee, Maggie]] (31 August 2013), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/aug/31/mr-loverman-bernardine-evaristo-review \"Mr Loverman by Bernardine Evaristo \u2013 review\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref><ref>[[Diriye Osman|Osman, Diriye]] (30 June 2014), [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/diriye-osman/mr-loverboy-book-review_b_5542202.html \"The Dazzling Story of an Older, Gay, Caribbean Dandy\"], ''HuffPost Queer Voices''.</ref> It won the Publishing Triangle [[Ferro-Grumley Award]] for LGBT Fiction (USA) and the [[Jerwood Fiction Uncovered Prize]].<ref name=\"Jerwood\">[http://jerwoodcharitablefoundation.org/jerwood-fiction-uncovered-prize The Jerwood Fiction Uncovered Prize], Jerwood Charitable Foundation.</ref> In 2015 she wrote and presented a two-part BBC Radio 4 documentary, ''Fiery Inspiration'' \u2013 on [[Amiri Baraka]] and his influence on her generation of writers.<ref>[http://www.brunel.ac.uk/cbass/arts-humanities/creativsere-writing/news-and-events/news/ne_450141 \"Bernadine Evaristo presents two-part show on BBC Radio 4\"], College of Business, Arts and Social Sciences, Brunel University London, 26 October 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06j1kdp ''Fiery Inspiration: Amiri Baraka and the black arts movement''], BBC Radio 4, 2015. Retrieved 2 August 2019.</ref>\n\nShe is a contributor to ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]: An international anthology of writing by women of African descent'' (2019), edited by [[Margaret Busby]].<ref name=BrittlePaper />\n\nEvaristo's most recent novel, ''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'' (May 2019, Hamish Hamilton/ Penguin UK), is an innovative polyvocal \"fusion fiction\"<ref>Tepper, Anderson, [https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/12/bernardine-evaristo-girl-woman-other-interview \"The Little Book That Could: How Bernardine Evaristo Became an International Writer-to-Watch in 2019\"], ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', 13 December 2019.</ref> about 12 primarily black British [[womxn]]. Their ages span 19 to 93 and they are a mix of cultural backgrounds, sexualities, classes and geographies, and the novel charts their hopes, struggles and intersecting lives. In July 2019 the novel was longlisted for the [[Booker Prize]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-49562607|title=Atwood and Rushdie on Booker Prize shortlist|date=3 September 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> and shortlisted for the 2019 [[Gordon Burn|Gordon Burn Prize]].<ref>Fraine, Laura (17 July 2019), [http://newwritingnorth.com/news/shortlist-announced-for-gordon-burn-prize-2019/ \"Shortlist announced for Gordon Burn Prize 2019\"], ''New Writing North''. Retrieved 29 July 2019.</ref> The novel was on the Booker Prize shortlist announced on 3 September 2019, alongside books by [[Margaret Atwood]], [[Lucy Ellmann]], [[Chigozie Obioma]], [[Salman Rushdie]] and [[Elif Shafak]],<ref>[https://thebookerprizes.com/news/2019-shortlist-has-been-announced \"The 2019 shortlist has been announced\"], The Booker Prizes, 3 September 2019.</ref> and on 14 October won the prize jointly with Atwood's ''[[The Testaments]]''.<ref name=\"Flood\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/oct/14/booker-prize-judges-break-the-rules-and-insist-on-joint-winners|title=Margaret Atwood and Bernardine Evaristo share Booker prize 2019|last=Flood|first=Alison|date=14 October 2019|access-date=14 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|website=The Guardian}}</ref> The win made her the first black woman and first black British author to win the prize.<ref name=\"Flood\" />\n\n==Teaching and touring==\nOther than at Brunel, Evaristo has taught creative writing since 1994. She has also been awarded many writing fellowships and residencies including the Montgomery Fellowship at [[Dartmouth College]], [[New Hampshire]], in 2015; for the British Council at [[Georgetown University]], Washington DC; [[Barnard College]]/ [[Columbia University]], New York; [[University of the Western Cape]], South Africa; the [[Virginia Arts Festival]] (Virginia, USA), and Writing Fellow at the [[University of East Anglia]], UK. She taught the University of East Anglia-''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' \"How to Tell a Story\" course for four seasons in London up to 2015.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nSince 1997, she has accepted more than 150 international invitations as a writer. These involve writer-residencies and visiting fellowships, [[British Council]] tours, book tours, teaching creative writing courses and workshops as well as keynotes, talks and panels at many conferences and literary festivals.<ref name=\"Official website\"/> She chaired the 32nd and 33rd [https://www.google.com/search?client=firefox-b-d&q=33RD+BERLIN+SEMINAR+BRITISH+COUNCIL British Council Berlin Literature Seminar] in 2017 and 2018. She has also toured the UK and regularly hosts and chairs events.<ref name=BrittlePaper>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2020/01/i-long-ago-chose-to-take-my-community-with-me-on-my-creative-journey-bernardine-evaristo/|title=I Long Ago Chose to Take My Community with Me on My Creative Journey {{!}} Bernardine Evaristo|last=|first=|date=2020-01-04|website=Brittle Paper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n==Critic and advocate==\nEvaristo has written many book reviews for UK publications, including ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/bernardine-evaristo Bernardine Evaristo profile] at ''The Guardian''.</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'' and the ''[[New Statesman]]''. Aside from founding the [[Brunel University African Poetry Prize|Brunel International African Poetry Prize]],<ref name=\"Official website\" /> in 2012 she was chair of judges for both the [[Caine Prize for African Writing]]<ref>[http://caineprize.blogspot.co.uk/2012/04/bernardineevaristo-chair-of-judges-2012.html \"Bernardine Evaristo, Chair of Judges 2012, writer and poet\"], Caine Prize, 23 April 2012.</ref> and the [[Commonwealth Short Story Prize]].<ref>Evaristo, Bernardine, [http://www.o.org/what-makes-a-good-short-story-by-bernardine-evaristo/ \"\u2018There is no magic formula\u2019\"] (Chair of the 2012 Commonwealth Short Story Prize on what makes a good short story) Commonwealth Writers.</ref> \n\nShe has also judged many other literary prizes including the [[Poetry Society]]'s [[National Poetry Competition]], [[Costa Book Awards]], the [[Goldsmiths Prize]], the [[T. S. Eliot Prize]], [[Orange Award for New Writers]] and [[Next Generation Poets]]. She is on the board of the African Poetry Book Fund<ref>[http://africanpoetrybf.unl.edu/sample-page-2/ Editorial Board], African Poetry Book Fund. Retrieved 16 October 2019.</ref> in the US, and judges all their prizes. She is a patron of the [[SI Leeds Literary Prize]].<ref>[http://sileedsliteraryprize.wordpress.com/patrons/ \"Patrons\"], SI Leeds Literary Prize. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113195227/http://sileedsliteraryprize.wordpress.com/patrons/ |date=13 November 2014 }}.</ref> In 2019 she is the judge of the Glenna Luschei Prize for African Poetry, and the Polari Book Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2020/01/i-long-ago-chose-to-take-my-community-with-me-on-my-creative-journey-bernardine-evaristo/|title=I Long Ago Chose to Take My Community with Me on My Creative Journey {{!}} Bernardine Evaristo|date=2020-01-04|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> \n\nIn 2006, Evaristo initiated an [[Arts Council England|Arts Council]]-funded report delivered by Spread the Word writer development agency into why black<ref>{{in lang|it}} Caponi, Paolo. ''Ester Gendusa, Identit\u00e0 nere e cultura europea. La narrativa di Bernardine Evaristo'', In: Altre Modernit\u00e0, Vol. 0, Iss. 14, pp. 211\u2013213 (2015).</ref> and Asian poets were not getting published in the UK, which revealed that less than 1% of all published poetry is by non-whites.<ref name=Advocacy/>\n\nWhen the report was published, she then initiated The Complete Works poetry mentoring scheme, with Nathalie Teitler and Spread the Word.<ref name=TCW/> Thirty poets were mentored, each over a one- or two-year period, and many are publishing books, winning many awards and receiving huge acclaim for their poetry.<ref>Ashenden, Amy (21 February 2014), [http://vadamagazine.com/entertainment/arts/bernardine-evaristo-interview \"Bernardine Evaristo \u2013 Interview\"], ''VADA''.</ref>\n\nEvaristo has also served on many key councils and advisory committees for various organisations including the Council of the Royal Society of Literature since 2017, the [[Arts Council of England]], the [[London Arts Board]], the British Council Literature Advisory Panel, the [[Society of Authors]], the [[Poetry Society]] (Chair) and ''Wasafiri'' international literature magazine.<ref name=\"Official website\"/>\n\nIn the 1980s, together with [[Paulette Randall]] and Patricia Hilaire, she founded [[Theatre of Black Women]],<ref name=UH /> the first theatre company in Britain of its kind. In the 1990s she organised Britain's first black British writing conference, held at the [[Museum of London]], and also Britain's first black British theatre conference, held at the [[Royal Festival Hall]]. In 1995 she co-founded and directed Spread the Word, London's writer development agency.<ref name=Advocacy>[https://bevaristo.com/advocacy/ \"Arts Advocacy\"], Bernardine Evaristo website.</ref>\n\nUpon winning the [[Booker Prize]], Evaristo dismissed the concept of [[cultural appropriation]], stating that it is ridiculous to expect writers not to \u201cwrite beyond your own culture.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanderson |first1=David |title=Booker winner Bernardine Evaristo writes off \u2018cultural appropriation\u2019 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/booker-winner-bernardine-evaristo-writes-off-cultural-appropriation-bklfsqhgk |accessdate=16 December 2019 |publisher=The Times |date=3 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours, awards, fellowships==\n* 2020: British Book Awards (finalist)\n* 2020: The Orwell Prize for Fiction (longlist)\n* 2020: The Glass Bell Awards (longlist)\n* 2020: Visionary Honours Awards (longlist)\n* 2020: Women's Prize for Fiction (longlist)\n* 2020: Australian Industry Book Awards (longlist)\n* 2020: Ferro Grumley Awards USA (finalist)\n* 2019: Gordon Burn Prize (finalist)\n* 2019: Winner of the [[Booker Prize]], October 2019<ref name=Flood />'''\n* 2018: Elected a Fellow, Rose Bruford College of Theatre & Performance<ref>[https://www.broadwayworld.com/westend/article/First-Rose-Bruford-College-Degrees-Awarded-20180917 \"First Rose Bruford College Degrees Awarded\"], ''Broadway World'', 17 September 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.bruford.ac.uk/about/fellows/ \"Fellows & Honorary Fellows\"], Rose Bruford College.</ref>\n* 2017: Elected a Fellow, the [[English Association]]<ref name=Brunel/>\n* 2015: Triangle Publishing Awards: The [[Ferro-Grumley Award]] for LGBT Fiction, USA<ref>[http://www.publishingtriangle.org/awards.asp Awards], The Publishing Triangle.</ref>\n* 2015:  The Montgomery Fellowship, Dartmouth College, USA<ref>[http://www.dartmouth.edu/~montfell/biographies/a_f/evaristo.html Bernardine Evaristo], Montgomery Fellows, Dartmouth College.</ref>\n* 2014: [[Jerwood Fiction Uncovered Prize]]<ref name=\"Jerwood\"/>\n* 2010: ''The Emperor's Babe'', ''The Times'' (UK) \"100 Best Books of the Decade\"<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-100-best-books-of-the-decade-952h76nd689 \"The 100 Best Books of the Decade\"], ''The Times'', 14 November 2009.</ref>\n* 2010: [[Hurston/Wright Legacy Award]], USA (finalist)<ref>[http://www.hurstonwright.org/authors/bernardine-evaristo/ \"Bernardine Evaristo\"], Hurston/Wright Foundation.</ref>\n* 2010: [[Poetry Book Society]] Commendation for ''Ten'', co-edited with [[Daljit Nagra]]<ref>[https://www.bloodaxebooks.com/ecs/product/ten-974 \"Bernardine Evaristo & Daljit Nagra: Ten\"], Bloodaxe Books.</ref>\n* 2009: [[International Dublin Literary Award]], nominated for ''Blonde Roots''<ref>[http://www.casadellapoesia.org/poeti/evaristo-bernardine-127 \"Bernardine Evaristo\"] at Casa della poesia.</ref>\n* 2009: ''Blonde Roots'', Big Red Read Award, Fiction and overall winner<ref>[https://www.allisonandbusby.com/info/2009/10/?cat=7 \"News & Events\"], Allison & Busby.</ref> \n* 2009: Awarded an [[MBE]] in the [[2009 Birthday Honours|Queen's Birthday Honours List]] for services to Literature<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/59090/supplement/1 \"No. 59090\"], ''The London Gazette'' (1st supplement), 12 June 2009, p. 16.</ref>\n* 2009: Orange Prize Youth Panel Choice for ''Blonde Roots''<ref>Guest, Katy (10 May 2009)[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/teenage-picks-six-teenagers-set-to-judge-orange-prize-alongside-the-regular-panel-1680137.html \"Teenage picks: Six teenagers set to judge Orange Prize alongside the regular panel\"]. ''Independent''. Retrieve d29 July 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.womensprizeforfiction.co.uk/about/new-writers \"2010 Judges\"], The Orange Award for New Writers.</ref>\n* 2009: [[Orange Prize]] for Fiction, nominated for ''Blonde Roots''<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/>\n* 2009: [[Arthur C. Clarke Award]], UK, nominated for ''Blonde Roots''<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/>\n* 2006: Elected a Fellow, [[Royal Society of Arts]]<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/> (est. 1754)\n* 2006: British Council Fellow, Georgetown University, USA<ref name=Encyclopedia>[https://www.encyclopedia.com/arts/educational-magazines/evaristo-bernardine-1959 \"Evaristo, Bernardine 1959\u2013\"], Encyclopedia.com.</ref>\n* 2004: Elected a Fellow, [[Royal Society of Literature]]<ref>[http://www.poetrysoc.com/content/mediaroom/pr20050402/ Poetry Society], 15 April 2005. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006083156/http://www.poetrysoc.com/content/mediaroom/pr20050402/ |date=6 October 2016 }}.</ref> (est. 1820)\n* 2003: [http://www.nesta.org.uk/about-us/our-history NESTA Fellowship Award (National Endowment of Science, Technology & The Arts)]\n* 2002: UEA Writing Fellow, University of East Anglia<ref>[https://www.uea.ac.uk/literature/creative-writing/faculty/previous-tutors/former-tutors-a-h \"Former Tutors A\u2013H\"], UEA.</ref>\n* 2000: Arts Council England Writer's Award 2000, for ''The Emperor\u2019s Babe''<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/>\n* 1999: [[Ethnic Multicultural Media Academy|EMMA Best Book Award]] for ''Lara''<ref name=Encyclopedia />\n\n==Bibliography==\n'''Books only'''\n*''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'', a novel (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2019, {{ISBN|978-0241364901}})\n*''[[Mr Loverman]]'', a novel (Penguin UK, 2013; Akashic Books, 2014, {{ISBN|978-1617752896}})\n*''[[Hello Mum]]'', a novella (Penguin UK, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0141044385}})\n*''Lara'' - new, expanded edition (Bloodaxe Books, 2009; {{ISBN|978-1852248314}})\n*''[[Blonde Roots]]'' (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2008; Riverhead/Penguin, USA, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0141031521}})\n*''[[Soul Tourists]]'' (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2005; {{ISBN|978-0140297829}})\n*''[[The Emperor's Babe]]'' (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2001; Penguin USA, 2002, {{ISBN|978-0140297812}})\n*''[[Lara (novel)|Lara]]'' (Angela Royal Publishing, 1997; {{ISBN|9781899860456}})\n*''Island of Abraham'' (Peepal Tree Press, 1994; {{ISBN|978-0948833601}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Bernadine Evaristo}}\n{{Wikiquote|Bernadine Evaristo}}\n* Curry, Ginette. [https://www.amazon.com/Literary-Representations-Mixed-Race-Characters-Diaspora/dp/1847182313 \"Toubab La!\": Literary Representations of Mixed-race Characters in the African Diaspora], Newcastle, England: Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2007.\n*[http://www.bevaristo.com Official website]\n*[https://www.curtisbrown.co.uk/client/bernardine-evaristo Bernardine Evaristo] at [[Curtis Brown (literary agents)|Curtis Brown]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071003023003/http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth179 \"Bernardine Evaristo\"], Contemporary Writers, British Council.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160427023247/http://www.bbawriting.com/bernardine-evaristo/ Bernardine Evaristo] at Diaspora Writers UK.\n*Toh Hsien Min, [http://www.qlrs.com/issues/jan2004/interviews/bevaristo.html \"Never Forgetting The Source \u2014 Bernardine Evaristo makes productive use of history\"] (interview), ''Quarterly Literary Review Singapore'', Vol. 3, No. 2, January 2004.\n\n{{Man Booker Prize|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evaristo, Bernardine}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:Academics of Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Goldsmiths, University of London]]\n[[Category:Booker Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n[[Category:English people of German descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:English people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women writers]]\n[[Category:British expatriate academics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Black British academics]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women academics]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Woolwich]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the English Association]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image         = Bernadine Evaristo.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| name          = Bernardine Evaristo\n|honorific_suffix =[[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]] [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]], [[English Association|FEA]]\n| caption       = Evaristo in 2008\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1959}}\n| birth_place   = [[London]], England, UK\n| birth_name    = Bernardine Anne Mobolaji Evaristo\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    = Novelist, critic, poet, playwright, academic\n| education     = [[Eltham Hill Grammar School|Eltham Hill Grammar School for Girls]]; [[Rose Bruford College of Speech and Drama]]; [[Goldsmiths College, University of London]]\n| nationality   = British\n| notable works =''[[Lara (novel)|Lara]]'' (1997)<br> ''[[The Emperor's Babe]]'' (2001)<br>''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'' (2019)\n| awards        = [[Booker Prize]], [[2019 Man Booker Prize|2019]]\n| website       = {{URL|https://bevaristo.com/}}\n}}\n'''Bernardine Evaristo''', [[Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]] [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]], [[English Association|FEA]] (born 1959), is a British author of eight works of fiction. Her bestselling novel, ''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'',<ref>[https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/311/311140/girl--woman--other/9780241364901.html ''Girl, Woman, Other''], Penguin.</ref> won the [[Man Booker Prize|Booker Prize]] in 2019. It was also one of Barack Obama's 19 Favourite Books of 2019. Evaristo's writing also includes short fiction, drama, poetry, essays, literary criticism, and projects for stage and radio. Two of her books, ''[[The Emperor's Babe]]'' (2001) and ''[[Hello Mum]]'' (2010), have been adapted into [[BBC Radio 4]] dramas. She is currently Professor of Creative Writing at [[Brunel University|Brunel University London]]<ref name=\"Brunel\">[http://www.brunel.ac.uk/people/bernardine-evaristo \"Bernardine Evaristo, Professor of Creative Writing\"], Brunel University London.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/sep/08/bernardine-evaristo-cultural-highlights|title=On My Radar: Bernadine Evaristo's cultural highlights|first=Ellie |last=Bothwell|date=8 September 2013|accessdate=9 September 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> and the vice-chair of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref>[https://rsliterature.org/about-us/council/ \"Council\"], The Royal Society of Literature. Retrieved 28 July 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Sethi\">{{cite news|last=Sethi|first=Anita|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/27/bernardine-evaristo-girl-woman-other-interview|title=Bernardine Evaristo: 'I want to put presence into absence'|work=The Guardian|date=27 April 2019|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nEvaristo is a longstanding advocate for the inclusion of writers and artists of colour. She founded the [[Brunel University African Poetry Prize]]<ref>[http://www.africanpoetryprize.org/ Brunel International African Poetry Prize] website.</ref> in 2012 and The Complete Works poets development scheme (2007\u20132017).<ref name=TCW>{{Cite web |url=https://thecompleteworkspoetry.com/ |title=The Complete Works |access-date=15 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216025030/https://thecompleteworkspoetry.com/ |archive-date=16 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She co-founded Spread the Word writer development agency<ref>[https://www.spreadtheword.org.uk/ \"About Us\"], Spread the Word.</ref> (1995\u2013present) and, in the 1980s, Britain's first black women's theatre company, [[Theatre of Black Women]].<ref name=UH>[https://www.unfinishedhistories.com/history/companies/theatre-of-black-women/ \"Theatre of Black Women\"], Unfinished Histories: Recording the History of Alternative Theatre. Retrieved 29 July 2019.</ref> She also organised Britain's first major black theatre conference, Future Histories, for the Black Theatre Forum,<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/companies/black-theatre-forum Black Theatre Forum]</ref> in 1995 in the [[Royal Festival Hall]], and Britain's first major conference on black British writing, ''Tracing Paper'', in 1997, at the [[Museum of London]].\n\n==Biography==\nEvaristo was born in [[Eltham]], south-east [[London]], and christened Bernardine Anne Mobolaji Evaristo.<ref>Harolds, Laolu (7 September 2019), [https://tribuneonlineng.com/two-nigerian-novelists-make-2019-booker-prize-shortlist/ \"Two Nigerian Novelists Make 2019 Booker Prize Shortlist\"], ''Nigerian Tribune''.</ref> She was raised in [[Woolwich]]. She is the fourth of eight children born to her white English mother, who was a schoolteacher, and her [[Nigerian]] father, who migrated to Britain in 1949 and became a welder and local [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] councillor.<ref name=\"Official website\">[http://bevaristo.com/ \"Bio\"], Author's website.</ref> Her paternal grandfather was a [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] Aguda or [[Saro (Nigeria)|Saro]] who returned from [[Brazil]] to Nigeria, and her paternal grandmother was from [[Abeokuta]] in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genevieveng.com/bernadine-evaristo-on-the-crossroads-of-culture/|title=Social: Bernadine Evaristo \u2026on the crossroads of culture|first=AdeOla |last=Fadumiye|website=Genevieve|accessdate=9 September 2014|url-status=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911003701/http://www.genevieveng.com/bernadine-evaristo-on-the-crossroads-of-culture/|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3591629/A-writers-life-Bernadine-Evaristo.html|title=A Writer's Life: Bernadine Evaristo|newspaper=The Telegraph|location=United Kingdom|date=23 March 2003|first=Tom |last=Payne|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Cambridge Introduction to Postcolonial Literatures in English|publisher =Cambridge University Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgeintrodu0000inne/page/68 68]|first=C. L. |last=Innes|isbn=978-1139-4655-95|accessdate=9 September 2014|url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgeintrodu0000inne|url-access=registration|quote=Bernardine Evaristo grandfather slave.|year=2007}}</ref> Her mother's paternal great-grandfather arrived in London from Germany in the 1860s and settled in Woolwich, south-east London, and her mother's maternal grandmother arrived in London from [[Ireland]] in the 1880s and settled in [[Islington]].<ref name=\"British Council\">[https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/bernardine-evaristo Bernardine Evaristo biography], British Council, Literature.</ref> Evaristo was educated at Greenwich Young People's Theatre (now the Tramshed, in Woolwich), [[Eltham Hill Grammar School|Eltham Hill Grammar School for Girls]], the [[Rose Bruford College of Speech and Drama]] and [[Goldsmiths College, University of London]], from where she received her doctorate in creative writing in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gold.ac.uk/our-people/profile-hub/english-and-comparative-literature/pg/other/bernardine-evaristo/|title=Bernardine Evaristo, Goldsmiths College|last= |first= |date= |website=gold.ac.uk|publisher=Goldsmiths University of London|access-date=16 October 2019|quote=}}</ref> In 2019 she was appointed Woolwich Laureate by the [[Greenwich+Docklands International Festival|Greenwich and Docklands International Festival]], reconnecting to and writing about the home town she left when she was 18.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/sep/07/bernardine-evaristo-made-in-woolwich|title=Bernardine Evaristo on Woolwich: 'We weren\u2019t allowed to play outside'|last= |first= |date=7 September 2019|website=theguardian.com|publisher=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=16 October 2019|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Writer and editor==\nEvaristo is the author of eight books of fiction and verse fiction that explore aspects of the [[African diaspora]].<ref name=Brunel/> She notably experiments with form and narrative perspective,<ref name=Brunel /> often merging the past with the present, fiction with poetry, the factual with the speculative, and reality with alternate realities (as in her 2008 novel ''[[Blonde Roots]]'').<ref>Merritt, Stephanie (24 August 2008), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/aug/24/fiction \"When slavery isn't such a black-and-white issue\"], ''The Observer''.</ref> Her verse novel ''The Emperor's Babe'' (Penguin, 2001) is about a black teenage girl whose parents are from [[Nubia]], who comes of age in Roman London nearly two thousand years ago.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} It won an [[Arts Council England|Arts Council]] Writers Award 2000; a [[Nesta (charity)|NESTA]] Fellowship Award in 2003; it was chosen by ''[[The Times]]'' as one of the \"100 Best Books of the Decade\" in 2010;<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-100-best-books-of-the-decade-952h76nd689 \"The 100 Best Books of the Decade\"], ''The Times'', 14 November 2009/</ref> and it was adapted into a [[BBC Radio 4]] play in 2013.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01sjjy3 ''The Emperor's Babe''], BBC Radio 4, 23 May 2013.</ref> Next she published ''[[Soul Tourists]]'' (Penguin, 2005), about a mismatched couple driving across Europe to the Middle East, which featured ghosts of real figures of colour from European history.<ref>[http://www.transculturalwriting.com/radiophonics/contents/writersonwriting/bernardineevaristo/soultourists-analysis/index.html \"Extract from ''Soul Tourists'' \u2014 Analysis\"], Crossing Borders.</ref><ref>Adams, Sarah (16 July 2005), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/jul/16/featuresreviews.guardianreview22 \"What a trip\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref>\n\nHer novel ''Blonde Roots'' (Penguin, 2008) is a satire that inverts the history of the [[transatlantic slave trade]] and replaces it with a universe where Africans enslave Europeans.<ref>[[Ron Charles (critic)|Charles, Ron]], [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/16/AR2009011600381.html \"Race Reversal\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 18 January 2009.</ref> ''Blonde Roots'' won the Orange Youth Panel Award and Big Red Read Award.<ref name=\"British Council\"/> Evaristo's other books include the verse novel ''[[Lara (novel)|Lara]]'' ([[Bloodaxe Books]], 2009, with an earlier version published in 1997), which fictionalised the multiple cultural strands of her family history going back over 150 years as well as her mixed-race London childhood.<ref>[http://www.bloodaxebooks.com/ecs/product/lara-927 Bernardine Evaristo, ''Lara''] at Bloodaxe Books.</ref> This won the [[Ethnic Multicultural Media Academy|EMMA Best Novel Award]] in 1998.<ref name=\"British Council\" /> Her novella ''Hello Mum'' (Penguin, 2010) was chosen as \"The Big Read\" for the [[County of Suffolk]], and adapted into a BBC Radio 4 play in 2012.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01l8rbj \"Hello Mum\"], ''Afternoon Drama'', BBC Radio 4, 3 August 2012.</ref>\n\nAs an editor, she guest-edited the September 2014 issue of ''[[Mslexia]]'' magazine, the [[Poetry Society|Poetry Society of Great Britain]]'s centenary winter issue of ''[[Poetry Review]]'' (2012), titled \"Offending Frequencies\"; a special issue of ''[[Wasafiri]]'' magazine called ''[[Black British|Black Britain]]: Beyond Definition'' (Routledge, 2010), with poet Karen McCarthy-Woolf; ''Ten'',<ref>[http://www.poetrybooks.co.uk/poetry_portal/ten_new_poets \"Ten New Poets by Bernardine Evaristo\"], Poetry Book Society. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426215058/http://www.poetrybooks.co.uk/poetry_portal/ten_new_poets |date=26 April 2014 }}.</ref> an anthology of Black and Asian poets, with poet [[Daljit Nagra]] (Bloodaxe Books, 2010) and in 2007, she co-edited the New Writing Anthology ''NW15'' ([[Granta]]/[[British Council]]). She was also editor of ''FrontSeat'' intercultural magazine in the 1990s,<ref name=\"Diaspora\">[http://www.bbawriting.com/bernardine-evaristo/ \"Bernardine Evaristo\"] at Diaspora Writers UK. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427023247/http://www.bbawriting.com/bernardine-evaristo/ |date=27 April 2016 }}.</ref> and one of the editors of ''Black Women Talk Poetry'' anthology (published in 1987 by the Black Womantalk Poetry collective of which Evaristo was part),<ref>Evaristo, Bernardine (19 October 2019), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/oct/19/bernadine-evaristo-what-a-time-to-be-a-black-british-womxn-writer \"Bernardine Evaristo: 'These are unprecedented times for black female writers'\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref> Britain's first such substantial anthology, featuring among its 20 poets [[Jackie Kay]], [[Dorothea Smartt]] and [[Adjoa Andoh]].<ref>Osborne, Deirdre (ed.) (2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=f48wDQAAQBAJ&pg=PR17&lpg=PR17&dq=%22%27Black+Women+Talk+Poetry%22+first+anthology&source=bl&ots=2mTjw3UiOF&sig=ACfU3U1D3ipRTXKvAC0ln3l5MKPXiagN0Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwito6rV8pbmAhUxTxUIHRDoDokQ6AEwA3oECC8QAQ#v=onepage&q=%22'Black%20Women%20Talk%20Poetry%22&f=false ''The Cambridge Companion to British Black and Asian Literature (1945\u20132010)''], Cambridge University Press, p. xvii.</ref>\n\nHer 2014 novel was ''Mr Loverman'' ([[Penguin Books|Penguin]] UK, 2013/ [[Akashic Books]] USA, 2014), about a septuagenarian Caribbean Londoner who is a [[closet homosexual]] and considering his options after a 50-year marriage to his wife.<ref>[[Maggie Gee (novelist)|Gee, Maggie]] (31 August 2013), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/aug/31/mr-loverman-bernardine-evaristo-review \"Mr Loverman by Bernardine Evaristo \u2013 review\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref><ref>[[Diriye Osman|Osman, Diriye]] (30 June 2014), [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/diriye-osman/mr-loverboy-book-review_b_5542202.html \"The Dazzling Story of an Older, Gay, Caribbean Dandy\"], ''HuffPost Queer Voices''.</ref> It won the Publishing Triangle [[Ferro-Grumley Award]] for LGBT Fiction (USA) and the [[Jerwood Fiction Uncovered Prize]].<ref name=\"Jerwood\">[http://jerwoodcharitablefoundation.org/jerwood-fiction-uncovered-prize The Jerwood Fiction Uncovered Prize], Jerwood Charitable Foundation.</ref> In 2015 she wrote and presented a two-part BBC Radio 4 documentary, ''Fiery Inspiration'' \u2013 on [[Amiri Baraka]] and his influence on her generation of writers.<ref>[http://www.brunel.ac.uk/cbass/arts-humanities/creativsere-writing/news-and-events/news/ne_450141 \"Bernadine Evaristo presents two-part show on BBC Radio 4\"], College of Business, Arts and Social Sciences, Brunel University London, 26 October 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06j1kdp ''Fiery Inspiration: Amiri Baraka and the black arts movement''], BBC Radio 4, 2015. Retrieved 2 August 2019.</ref>\n\nShe is a contributor to ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]: An international anthology of writing by women of African descent'' (2019), edited by [[Margaret Busby]].<ref name=BrittlePaper />\n\nEvaristo's most recent novel, ''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'' (May 2019, Hamish Hamilton/ Penguin UK), is an innovative polyvocal \"fusion fiction\"<ref>Tepper, Anderson, [https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/12/bernardine-evaristo-girl-woman-other-interview \"The Little Book That Could: How Bernardine Evaristo Became an International Writer-to-Watch in 2019\"], ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', 13 December 2019.</ref> about 12 primarily black British [[womxn]]. Their ages span 19 to 93 and they are a mix of cultural backgrounds, sexualities, classes and geographies, and the novel charts their hopes, struggles and intersecting lives. In July 2019 the novel was longlisted for the [[Booker Prize]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-49562607|title=Atwood and Rushdie on Booker Prize shortlist|date=3 September 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> and shortlisted for the 2019 [[Gordon Burn|Gordon Burn Prize]].<ref>Fraine, Laura (17 July 2019), [http://newwritingnorth.com/news/shortlist-announced-for-gordon-burn-prize-2019/ \"Shortlist announced for Gordon Burn Prize 2019\"], ''New Writing North''. Retrieved 29 July 2019.</ref> The novel was on the Booker Prize shortlist announced on 3 September 2019, alongside books by [[Margaret Atwood]], [[Lucy Ellmann]], [[Chigozie Obioma]], [[Salman Rushdie]] and [[Elif Shafak]],<ref>[https://thebookerprizes.com/news/2019-shortlist-has-been-announced \"The 2019 shortlist has been announced\"], The Booker Prizes, 3 September 2019.</ref> and on 14 October won the prize jointly with Atwood's ''[[The Testaments]]''.<ref name=\"Flood\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/oct/14/booker-prize-judges-break-the-rules-and-insist-on-joint-winners|title=Margaret Atwood and Bernardine Evaristo share Booker prize 2019|last=Flood|first=Alison|date=14 October 2019|access-date=14 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|website=The Guardian}}</ref> The win made her the first black woman and first black British author to win the prize.<ref name=\"Flood\" />\n\n==Teaching and touring==\nOther than at Brunel, Evaristo has taught creative writing since 1994. She has also been awarded many writing fellowships and residencies including the Montgomery Fellowship at [[Dartmouth College]], [[New Hampshire]], in 2015; for the British Council at [[Georgetown University]], Washington DC; [[Barnard College]]/ [[Columbia University]], New York; [[University of the Western Cape]], South Africa; the [[Virginia Arts Festival]] (Virginia, USA), and Writing Fellow at the [[University of East Anglia]], UK. She taught the University of East Anglia-''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' \"How to Tell a Story\" course for four seasons in London up to 2015.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nSince 1997, she has accepted more than 150 international invitations as a writer. These involve writer-residencies and visiting fellowships, [[British Council]] tours, book tours, teaching creative writing courses and workshops as well as keynotes, talks and panels at many conferences and literary festivals.<ref name=\"Official website\"/> She chaired the 32nd and 33rd [https://www.google.com/search?client=firefox-b-d&q=33RD+BERLIN+SEMINAR+BRITISH+COUNCIL British Council Berlin Literature Seminar] in 2017 and 2018. She has also toured the UK and regularly hosts and chairs events.<ref name=BrittlePaper>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2020/01/i-long-ago-chose-to-take-my-community-with-me-on-my-creative-journey-bernardine-evaristo/|title=I Long Ago Chose to Take My Community with Me on My Creative Journey {{!}} Bernardine Evaristo|last=|first=|date=2020-01-04|website=Brittle Paper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n==Critic and advocate==\nEvaristo has written many book reviews for UK publications, including ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/bernardine-evaristo Bernardine Evaristo profile] at ''The Guardian''.</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'' and the ''[[New Statesman]]''. Aside from founding the [[Brunel University African Poetry Prize|Brunel International African Poetry Prize]],<ref name=\"Official website\" /> in 2012 she was chair of judges for both the [[Caine Prize for African Writing]]<ref>[http://caineprize.blogspot.co.uk/2012/04/bernardineevaristo-chair-of-judges-2012.html \"Bernardine Evaristo, Chair of Judges 2012, writer and poet\"], Caine Prize, 23 April 2012.</ref> and the [[Commonwealth Short Story Prize]].<ref>Evaristo, Bernardine, [http://www.o.org/what-makes-a-good-short-story-by-bernardine-evaristo/ \"\u2018There is no magic formula\u2019\"] (Chair of the 2012 Commonwealth Short Story Prize on what makes a good short story) Commonwealth Writers.</ref> \n\nShe has also judged many other literary prizes including the [[Poetry Society]]'s [[National Poetry Competition]], [[Costa Book Awards]], the [[Goldsmiths Prize]], the [[T. S. Eliot Prize]], [[Orange Award for New Writers]] and [[Next Generation Poets]]. She is on the board of the African Poetry Book Fund<ref>[http://africanpoetrybf.unl.edu/sample-page-2/ Editorial Board], African Poetry Book Fund. Retrieved 16 October 2019.</ref> in the US, and judges all their prizes. She is a patron of the [[SI Leeds Literary Prize]].<ref>[http://sileedsliteraryprize.wordpress.com/patrons/ \"Patrons\"], SI Leeds Literary Prize. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113195227/http://sileedsliteraryprize.wordpress.com/patrons/ |date=13 November 2014 }}.</ref> In 2019 she is the judge of the Glenna Luschei Prize for African Poetry, and the Polari Book Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brittlepaper.com/2020/01/i-long-ago-chose-to-take-my-community-with-me-on-my-creative-journey-bernardine-evaristo/|title=I Long Ago Chose to Take My Community with Me on My Creative Journey {{!}} Bernardine Evaristo|date=2020-01-04|website=Brittle Paper|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> \n\nIn 2006, Evaristo initiated an [[Arts Council England|Arts Council]]-funded report delivered by Spread the Word writer development agency into why black<ref>{{in lang|it}} Caponi, Paolo. ''Ester Gendusa, Identit\u00e0 nere e cultura europea. La narrativa di Bernardine Evaristo'', In: Altre Modernit\u00e0, Vol. 0, Iss. 14, pp. 211\u2013213 (2015).</ref> and Asian poets were not getting published in the UK, which revealed that less than 1% of all published poetry is by non-whites.<ref name=Advocacy/>\n\nWhen the report was published, she then initiated The Complete Works poetry mentoring scheme, with Nathalie Teitler and Spread the Word.<ref name=TCW/> Thirty poets were mentored, each over a one- or two-year period, and many are publishing books, winning many awards and receiving huge acclaim for their poetry.<ref>Ashenden, Amy (21 February 2014), [http://vadamagazine.com/entertainment/arts/bernardine-evaristo-interview \"Bernardine Evaristo \u2013 Interview\"], ''VADA''.</ref>\n\nEvaristo has also served on many key councils and advisory committees for various organisations including the Council of the Royal Society of Literature since 2017, the [[Arts Council of England]], the [[London Arts Board]], the British Council Literature Advisory Panel, the [[Society of Authors]], the [[Poetry Society]] (Chair) and ''Wasafiri'' international literature magazine.<ref name=\"Official website\"/>\n\nIn the 1980s, together with [[Paulette Randall]] and Patricia Hilaire, she founded [[Theatre of Black Women]],<ref name=UH /> the first theatre company in Britain of its kind. In the 1990s she organised Britain's first black British writing conference, held at the [[Museum of London]], and also Britain's first black British theatre conference, held at the [[Royal Festival Hall]]. In 1995 she co-founded and directed Spread the Word, London's writer development agency.<ref name=Advocacy>[https://bevaristo.com/advocacy/ \"Arts Advocacy\"], Bernardine Evaristo website.</ref>\n\nUpon winning the [[Booker Prize]], Evaristo dismissed the concept of [[cultural appropriation]], stating that it is ridiculous to expect writers not to \u201cwrite beyond your own culture.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanderson |first1=David |title=Booker winner Bernardine Evaristo writes off \u2018cultural appropriation\u2019 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/booker-winner-bernardine-evaristo-writes-off-cultural-appropriation-bklfsqhgk |accessdate=16 December 2019 |publisher=The Times |date=3 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours, awards, fellowships==|\n* 2020: British Book Awards (finalist)\n* 2020: The Orwell Prize for Fiction (longlist)\n* 2020: The Glass Bell Awards (longlist)\n* 2020: Visionary Honours Awards (longlist)\n* 2020: Womens Prize for Fiction (longlist)\n* 2020: Australian Industry Book Awards (longlist)\n* 2020: Ferro Grumley Awards USA (finalist)\n* 2019: Gordon Burn Prize (finalist)\n* 2019: Winner of the [[Booker Prize]], October 2019<ref name=Flood />'''\n* 2018: Elected a Fellow, Rose Bruford College of Theatre & Performance<ref>[https://www.broadwayworld.com/westend/article/First-Rose-Bruford-College-Degrees-Awarded-20180917 \"First Rose Bruford College Degrees Awarded\"], ''Broadway World'', 17 September 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.bruford.ac.uk/about/fellows/ \"Fellows & Honorary Fellows\"], Rose Bruford College.</ref>\n* 2017: Elected a Fellow, the [[English Association]]<ref name=Brunel/>\n* 2015: Triangle Publishing Awards: The [[Ferro-Grumley Award]] for LGBT Fiction, USA<ref>[http://www.publishingtriangle.org/awards.asp Awards], The Publishing Triangle.</ref>\n* 2015:  The Montgomery Fellowship, Dartmouth College, USA<ref>[http://www.dartmouth.edu/~montfell/biographies/a_f/evaristo.html Bernardine Evaristo], Montgomery Fellows, Dartmouth College.</ref>\n* 2014: [[Jerwood Fiction Uncovered Prize]]<ref name=\"Jerwood\"/>\n* 2010: ''The Emperor's Babe'', ''The Times'' (UK) \"100 Best Books of the Decade\"<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-100-best-books-of-the-decade-952h76nd689 \"The 100 Best Books of the Decade\"], ''The Times'', 14 November 2009.</ref>\n* 2010: [[Hurston/Wright Legacy Award]], USA (finalist)<ref>[http://www.hurstonwright.org/authors/bernardine-evaristo/ \"Bernardine Evaristo\"], Hurston/Wright Foundation.</ref>\n* 2010: [[Poetry Book Society]] Commendation for ''Ten'', co-edited with [[Daljit Nagra]]<ref>[https://www.bloodaxebooks.com/ecs/product/ten-974 \"Bernardine Evaristo & Daljit Nagra: Ten\"], Bloodaxe Books.</ref>\n* 2009: [[International Dublin Literary Award]], nominated for ''Blonde Roots''<ref>[http://www.casadellapoesia.org/poeti/evaristo-bernardine-127 \"Bernardine Evaristo\"] at Casa della poesia.</ref>\n* 2009: ''Blonde Roots'', Big Red Read Award, Fiction and overall winner<ref>[https://www.allisonandbusby.com/info/2009/10/?cat=7 \"News & Events\"], Allison & Busby.</ref> \n* 2009: Awarded an [[MBE]] in the [[2009 Birthday Honours|Queen's Birthday Honours List]] for services to Literature<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/59090/supplement/1 \"No. 59090\"], ''The London Gazette'' (1st supplement), 12 June 2009, p. 16.</ref>\n* 2009: Orange Prize Youth Panel Choice for ''Blonde Roots''<ref>Guest, Katy (10 May 2009)[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/teenage-picks-six-teenagers-set-to-judge-orange-prize-alongside-the-regular-panel-1680137.html \"Teenage picks: Six teenagers set to judge Orange Prize alongside the regular panel\"]. ''Independent''. Retrieve d29 July 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.womensprizeforfiction.co.uk/about/new-writers \"2010 Judges\"], The Orange Award for New Writers.</ref>\n* 2009: [[Orange Prize]] for Fiction, nominated for ''Blonde Roots''<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/>\n* 2009: [[Arthur C. Clarke Award]], UK, nominated for ''Blonde Roots''<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/>\n* 2006: Elected a Fellow, [[Royal Society of Arts]]<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/> (est. 1754)\n* 2006: British Council Fellow, Georgetown University, USA<ref name=Encyclopedia>[https://www.encyclopedia.com/arts/educational-magazines/evaristo-bernardine-1959 \"Evaristo, Bernardine 1959\u2013\"], Encyclopedia.com.</ref>\n* 2004: Elected a Fellow, [[Royal Society of Literature]]<ref>[http://www.poetrysoc.com/content/mediaroom/pr20050402/ Poetry Society], 15 April 2005. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006083156/http://www.poetrysoc.com/content/mediaroom/pr20050402/ |date=6 October 2016 }}.</ref> (est. 1820)\n* 2003: [http://www.nesta.org.uk/about-us/our-history NESTA Fellowship Award (National Endowment of Science, Technology & The Arts)]\n* 2002: UEA Writing Fellow, University of East Anglia<ref>[https://www.uea.ac.uk/literature/creative-writing/faculty/previous-tutors/former-tutors-a-h \"Former Tutors A\u2013H\"], UEA.</ref>\n* 2000: Arts Council England Writer's Award 2000, for ''The Emperor\u2019s Babe''<ref name=\"Diaspora\"/>\n* 1999: [[Ethnic Multicultural Media Academy|EMMA Best Book Award]] for ''Lara''<ref name=Encyclopedia />\n\n==Bibliography==\n'''Books only'''\n*''[[Girl, Woman, Other]]'', a novel (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2019, {{ISBN|978-0241364901}})\n*''[[Mr Loverman]]'', a novel (Penguin UK, 2013; Akashic Books, 2014, {{ISBN|978-1617752896}})\n*''[[Hello Mum]]'', a novella (Penguin UK, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0141044385}})\n*''Lara'' - new, expanded edition (Bloodaxe Books, 2009; {{ISBN|978-1852248314}})\n*''[[Blonde Roots]]'' (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2008; Riverhead/Penguin, USA, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0141031521}})\n*''[[Soul Tourists]]'' (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2005; {{ISBN|978-0140297829}})\n*''[[The Emperor's Babe]]'' (Hamish Hamilton/Penguin, 2001; Penguin USA, 2002, {{ISBN|978-0140297812}})\n*''[[Lara (novel)|Lara]]'' (Angela Royal Publishing, 1997; {{ISBN|9781899860456}})\n*''Island of Abraham'' (Peepal Tree Press, 1994; {{ISBN|978-0948833601}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Bernadine Evaristo}}\n{{Wikiquote|Bernadine Evaristo}}\n* Curry, Ginette. [https://www.amazon.com/Literary-Representations-Mixed-Race-Characters-Diaspora/dp/1847182313 \"Toubab La!\": Literary Representations of Mixed-race Characters in the African Diaspora], Newcastle, England: Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2007.\n*[http://www.bevaristo.com Official website]\n*[https://www.curtisbrown.co.uk/client/bernardine-evaristo Bernardine Evaristo] at [[Curtis Brown (literary agents)|Curtis Brown]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071003023003/http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth179 \"Bernardine Evaristo\"], Contemporary Writers, British Council.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160427023247/http://www.bbawriting.com/bernardine-evaristo/ Bernardine Evaristo] at Diaspora Writers UK.\n*Toh Hsien Min, [http://www.qlrs.com/issues/jan2004/interviews/bevaristo.html \"Never Forgetting The Source \u2014 Bernardine Evaristo makes productive use of history\"] (interview), ''Quarterly Literary Review Singapore'', Vol. 3, No. 2, January 2004.\n\n{{Man Booker Prize|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evaristo, Bernardine}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:Academics of Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Goldsmiths, University of London]]\n[[Category:Booker Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n[[Category:English people of German descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:English people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women writers]]\n[[Category:British expatriate academics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Black British academics]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women academics]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Woolwich]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the English Association]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Arts]]\n", "name_user": "Cavie78", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernardine_Evaristo"}
